Cargo :
^^^^^
cargo is rust's build system and package manager.
it handles code dependencies.

create new project with cargo
    cargo new <project-name>
this will create a new directory named <project-name>.
in which directory,a file name "Cargo.toml" is created,the file describes the
project information,such package version,dependencies,etc.
and a subdirectory named "src" is creaded,that is the place where source code files
in. // for hello world project,it automatically create main.rs file,and contains
    // full code used to print "hello,world".

we can specify the version control system through command line parameter "--vcs=".
if we have specified vcs,it will automatically initializes the vcs.
// for git,execute "git init".

command "init" of cargo
    help us to initialize cargo for a been exist project that without cargo has
    associated.
command "build" of cargo
    ask cargo build the project,this will produces a lot of files needed by the
    project,moreover,it will produces an binary executable file of debug version
    of this project.the built files are placed under the subdirectory "target".
    in default,cargo will build debug version of executable.with the parameter
    "--release",it will build release version of executable,that means no
    debug information is contained.
command "run" of cargo
    ask cargo build and run the binary executable file of this project.
command "check" of cargo
    quickly checks code to make sure it compiles but does not produce an executable.

Variables and Mutability :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

keyword "let" is used to declare a variable.by default,all variable is immutable,but
we can change it to mutable by use keyword "mut".
    let x = 5;      // immutable,default
    let mut x = 5;  // mutable
if a variable is immutable,then we can not modify its value later,we can only specify
the value for it at initialization time.if we did this,"rustc" will refuse to
compiles it and throws error mesage.
// in C and C++,variable is mutable by default,keyword "const" is used to declare
// a constant.we can also cast away the const,but actually compiler just create
// a new temporary object same as the old object without "const" specifier.
! if we want to defer the variable bound for an immutable variable,we can just
  declare the variable without initialize it.
  the immutable binding will happens at the first time assign a value to this
  variable.
  in other word,immutable variable can only be assigned once,but the time can be
  deferred.

keyword "const" is used to declare a constant.a constant is not immutable by default,
it is always immutable.
    const CONSTANT_VALUE: u32 = 10 + 20;
    |     |               |     |
    |     |               |     +--> constant initialization expression
    |     |               +--> data type
    |     +--> object name
    +--> const keyword
constant may be set only to a constant expression,that means its value must be
determined during compile time,not at the runtime.
the lifetime of constant is valid for the entire time a program runs,within the 
scope in which it were declared.
! constant expression means,can not includes any variables.

rust allows "shadowing",that is permit redefine the variable several times,the last
definition will mask the previous definitions,and they are called shadowed by the
next definition.
    let x = 5;          // shadowed by the second definition
    let x = x + 1;      // shadowed by the third definition
    let x = x + 1 + 1;  // the last,overshadows previous definitions
note that,shadowing has scope limitation,that means if the overshadow definition
is defined in a compound statement.its shadowing is only valid in that scope.
    let x = 2;      // @x == 2
    let x = x + 1;  // now @x == 3
    {
        // inner scope
        let x = 5;  // now @x == 5
    }
    // now @x == 3
! shadowing is finished during compile time.
  by use shadowing,we can modify the initial value of an immutable variable
  during compile time.
  and because the data type is automatically deduced from initializer,so we
  can let the variable to represent different data with different type as well.
        let x = 2;                           // integer
        let x = String::from("hello world"); // string
  ! we can not do the same at mutable variable,because its data type is determined
    at the first time when it is bound to a value.
  ! we can overshadow the old definition that is mutable with an immutable definition,
    conversely also is OK.
        let mut x = 10; // mutable @x.
        let x = 20;     // overshadow "mut x",now is immutable @x.

Data Types :
^^^^^^^^^^

every value in rust is of a certain data type,rust use the type to determines what
the object it is and what operations can be done on them.
! rust is a statically typed language,all types of all variables must be known
  at compile time.
some types may support type-conversions.

scalar types >
    a scalar type represents a single value.
    rust has four primary scalar types: integer,floating-point,boolean,character.

integer types >
    i8, u8          =>   8-bit
    i16, u16        =>   16-bit
    i32, u32        =>   32-bit
    i64, u64        =>   64-bit
    i128, u128      =>   128-bit
    isize, usize    =>   architecture-dependent

    i: signed integer
    u: unsigned integer

    default integer type is i32.
    '-' means minus value,'+' can be omitted.

    integer literals:
        10  10_22       decimal
        0xff            hex
        0o52            octal
        0b1111_0000     binary
        b'C'            byte(u8 only)

        symbol '_' as visual separator for better readability.
        0x, 0o, 0b, b as prefix.

    representation: 2's complement
    overflow: wrap around

    ! for release version,rust compiler do not processes integer overflow checking.
      for debug version,compiler will throws error and panic.
      some useful standard library features:
        wrapping_* methods => wrap in all modes // release or debug
        checked_* methods => return the None value if overflow
        overflowing_* methods => return the value and a boolean indicating
                                 whether there was overflow
        saturating_* methods => saturate at the value's minimum or maximum values

floating-point types >
    f32     =>      32-bit floating-point (single precision)
    f64     =>      64-bit floating-point (double precision)

    default floating-point type is f64.

numeric operations >
    +   =>  addition
    -   =>  substraction
    *   =>  multiplication
    /   =>  division        // floor to the result
    %   =>  remainder

    ()  =>  parenthesis for adjust priority

    !! NUMBERIC OPERATIONS FOR DIFFERENT TYPES CAN NOT BE MIXED.
       FOR EXAMPLE,WE CAN NOT ADD AN INTEGER OBJECT TO A FLOATINTG-POINT OBJECT.

boolean types >
    bool    => 1 byte
        true    =>  T
        false   =>  F

character type >
    char    =>  4 bytes,represents a Unicode scalar value,can represents a lot
                more than just ASCII.

    single quotation '' means the value is a character.
    // for string,that is "".

compound types >
    compound types can group multiple values into one type,and rust has two
    primitive compound types: tuples and arrays.

tuple type >
    similar to std::tuple<> in C++,rust also can let an object to contains several
    values have different types.
    use the parenthesis symbol to represent tuple type:
        let tup: (i32. f32, char) = (20, 3.2, 'x');
    this statement declares an immutable variable named @tup,its type is the
    compound type composed by types i32,f32,char,and initialize it to
    (20, 3.2, 'x').
    a tuple is considered a single compound element.
    to get individual values in the compound type:
        let [x, y, z] = tup;
    // in C++,we can use
    //     auto [x, y, z] = struct_object;
    // to do the same.
    // but for std::tuple<>,for get the individual value,
    // we must use
    //     std::get<N>(std::tuple<> object);

    we can also access a tuple element directly by using a period(.) followed by
    the index of the value we want to access:
      let x = tup.0;    // the first value has index 0
      let y = tup.1;
      let z = tup.2;
      // similar to the member accessor in C/C++.

    ! if we want to pass a tuple to a function as its parameter,then we can
          fn func(t: (<type1>, <type2>, ...)) { }
          fn func(t: &(<type1>, <type2>, ...)) { }
          fn func((x, y): (<type1>, <type2>)) { }

array type >
    an array is a collection of values have the same type.
    for declare an array,we can do:
        let a = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
    this will declare variable @a is type of an array of i32 type,and the array
    size is 5.
    the first element in an array has index 0.
    except integer array,we can also define string array:
        let strings = ["one", "two", "three"];
    others as the same.

    if we want to explicitly specify the underlying type of array's elements,
    we can do:
        let a: [f32; 5] = [1.0, 1.2, 1.4, 1.6, 2.0];
            |  | | | |     |
            |  | | | |     +--> initializer-list
            |  | | | +--> size of array
            |  | | +--> delimiter
            |  | +--> floating-point 32-bit
            |  +--> compound type,array
            +--> object name

    we can also omit the underlying type,instead,we initialize the array with all
    elements have the same value:
        let a = [2; 10];
    this will declare an array has 10 elements,and each of them is initialized to
    value 2,thus the underlying type is i32.
    ! other type is OK.

    for access an element in array,we can use the syntax:
        @a[@index]
    to access it.
    
    ! if we access to an array with a invalid index at runtime,the thread which
      did that will throw error and panicked.
      if we specify the index to an array with a constant,then this error will be
      detected by compiler during compile time.
    ! if we want a function to receive an array as its parameter,then we can
          fn func(ary: &[<type>]) {
              ...
          }

Functions :
^^^^^^^^^

keyword "fn" is used to declare a function.
    fn the_func() {
        ...
    }

of course,functions can receive some parameters,and these parameters is placed in
parenthesis of the function,as parameter list.
    fn the_func(x: i32) {
        ...
    }

where @x is the name of parameter,i32 is the type of @x,this is same as variable
declare in function's body.
if there is several parameters,we need to use comma ',' symbol to separate them.
    fn the_func(x: i32, y: f32) {
        ...
    }
note that,the parameters of a function can only be seen in the function's body,
that is the scope of that function.called local variable.

function can be called through the function's name and some parameters(if have).
    the_func(2, 3.2);

function body is made up of a series of statements optionally ending in an
expression.
rust is an expression-based language,in which
    statements are instructions that perform some action and do not return a value
    expressions evaluate to a resultant value
expressions do not invlude ending semicolons,but statements have one.
function definitions are also statements.
calling a function is an expression.
calling a macro is an expression.
a new scope block created with curly brackets is an expression.
    let x = {
        let y = 3;
        y + 1   // an expression,because no ending semicolon.
    }; // @x will be set to 4.

because calling to a function is an expression,thus function can return values
as its result.
    fn add(x: i32, y: i32) -> i32 {
        x + y   // expression
    } // similar to trailing return in C++.

keyword "return" is used to return from current function,it can be followed by
an expression,as the result of this function evaluate.
    fn the_func() -> i32 {
        return 32;
    }
    // because function calling is expression,we can use the calling in variable
    // initialization,or other somewhere.


Comments :
^^^^^^^^

line comment which turns the context in an line to comment.
    // ...

block comment which turns the context in a block to comment.
    /* ... */

Control Flow :
^^^^^^^^^^^^

if expressions >
    if @predicate {
        // branch A
    } else {
        // branch B
    }

    if @predicate {
        // branch A
    } else if @predicate {
        // branch B
    } else {
        // branch C
    }

    if @predicate {
        // branch A
    }

    (@condition)
    @predicate is a boolean value,or a logic expression,
    which will produce a boolean value.
        X > Y
        X < Y
        X == Y
        X != Y
        true
        false

    if expression will only executes one branch, where @predicate is the
    first predicate is true.

    we can combine "let" and "if expression.
        let x = if @predicate { @expression1 } else { @expression2 };

    ! different from C and C++,the @predicate(or,@condition) is not inclued in
      parenthesis.and each branch must be included in the block.

loops >
    keyword "loop" used to processes infinity loop,no stop condition at there.
        loop {
            println!("again.");
        }
    but keyword "break" can be used break current loop.(only current loop-level)
        let mut x = 0;
        loop {
            if x > 3 {
                break;
            }
        }
    we also can let an expression follows "break",the expression will be evaluated
    when the loop is going to be broken,and the result of the expression is the
    result of this loop expression.
        let mut x = 0;
        loop {
            if x > 3 {
                break x + 5;
            }

            x += 1;
        }

    keyword "continue" can be used in loop expression,when the "continue" statement
    is executed,the rest of current loop would not be executed.instead,the control
    flow will skip the rest and get into next iteration.
        let mut x = 3;
        loop {
            continue;
            x += 1;     // this statement will never be executed.
        }

    we can set a label for a loop,and the label can be used later in the nested
    loop expression,by the "break" keyword or the "continue" keyword.
        'loop_label: loop {

        } // this will set "'loop_label" as the label of this loop,in other word,
          // name it.

        'loop_1: loop {
            'loop_2: loop {
                break 'loop_1;

                'loop_3: loop {
                    break 'loop_2;
                }
            }
        }
    ! loop label must started with a quote symbol "'".
    ! current loop can only see the loop label of front-level loop.
          'loop_1: loop {
                  continue 'loop_2; // ERROR
              'loop_2: loop {
                  ...
              }
          }
    ! in C style >
          loop_1:
                  loop {
          loop_2:
                          loop {
                                  goto loop_1;
                          }       // continue 'loop_1;
                  }
      but in rust,only "jmp <symbol>b" is allowed in nested cycle.

    keyword "while" can be used to execute a loop,but different from keyword "loop",
    if has a stop condition.
        let mut x = 0;
        while x != 100 {
            ...
        }
    the while loop expression will only be evaluated if the @predicate is true,
    if the @predicate is false,the expression would not be evaluated.
    we can use true as the @predicate,to let while-loop behaves same as loop.
    
    keyword "for" can be used to looping through a collection,it can iterates each
    element in a given range,and will stops when all elements have been iterated.
        let x = [5; 10];    // an array
        for e in x {
            println("element is {e}.");
        }
    where @e is a local variable,it used by "for" to bind elements from a given
    range,and its lifetime will ends when "for" is stopped.
    ! standard libarary provides 'Range' infrastructure,it can be used to 
      generate a collection of numbers from a given range,and it can be used
      combined with for-loop.
          for v in (1..100).rev() {
              println!("v is {v}.");
          } // for each number in range [1, 100),in reverse order.
                                       #^half-open
      ! if we want reverse order,must use .rev().
        such the range (100..1) is an error,and the range 100..1 will no number collection
        is produced.(the for-loop will just be skipped)


    if we use for with an array,it can iterates each element in that array.
    but if we use it with a range of numbers,the range will be half-open by default.
        for v in 1..50 {

        } // half-open,range [1, 50)
    if we need inclusive range,must use '=' symbole before the end point.
        for v in 1..=50 {

        } // inclusive range,range [1, 50]

Understanding Ownership :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

the base feature of rust for memory safety.

ownership is a set of rules that govern how a rust program manages memory.
in rust,memory is managed through a system of ownership with a set of rules that
the compiler checks.must all rule checks are passed,the program would be compiled.

ownership rules >
    each value in rust has an owner.
    there can only be one owner at a time.
    when the owner goest out of scope,the value will be dropped.

variable scope >
    a scope is the range within a program for which an item is valid.
    local variable is valid in its declaration scope.

The String type >
    String type manages data allocated on the heap,and as such is able to store
    an amount of text that is unknown to us at compile time.
        let s = String::from("nil"); // declare an immutable variable @s.
                                     // initialize @s to String type with
                                     // text "nil".
        let mut s2 = String::from("Hello"); // mutable variable
        s2.push_str(",World");  // @s2 => "Hello,World"

for a string literal,the text is hardcoded,we know the contents at compile time.
hence,we can not modify string literal during runtime,and the size of this blob
object must be known at compile time.

String support a mutable,growable piece of text,the size of contents is unknown
at compile time.
so
    the memory must be requested from the memory allocator at runtime.
    we need a way of returning this memory to the allocator when we are
    done with the String object.

for the language with GC,GC will handles memory free.
for the language without GC,programmer must free it explicitly.
rust has not GC,but in rust,the memory is automatically returned once the variable
that owns it goes out of scope. /* C++ automatically destructor,RAII */
when a variable goes out to its scope,rust calls a special function,which is
called drop().in that function,author of local variable(on heap) can put the
code to return the memory.
// rust calls drop() automatically at the closing curly bracket.

for variable bound to a value is known,fixed size,assign such variable to another
variable,rust will simply copy it and pushed onto the stack.
    let x = 5;  // bind 5 to @x,on stack
    let y = x;  // makeup @y,copy @x to @y,on stack
                // the value is known at compile time.
    ! stack-only data,copy it,and this copying is happened at compile time.
      only shallowing copy,but that is the all thing.

but for variable bound to a heap memory,assign such variable to another variable,
rust considers the previous variable as no longer valid,and the second variable
will becomes the owner of that heap memory.when these two variables go out of
scope,only the second variable will be dropped.
! object's meta information is stored on stack,in which a pointer
  points to the heap memory where stored the data.
  for example.the String type,it may be looks like
      name          object-name
      ptr           0x????????? -------> [ 0x???01 | 0x???02 | 0x???03 | ... ]
      len           ? -----------------> |<---------- in-use --------->|
      capability    ? -----------------> |<-------------- all -------------->|
      |<------- meta -------->|          |<--------- heap memory ----------->|
       # on stack
! in C++,such assignment is called move semantics.
  if an object is moved,that called the second object "steal" the inner of
  the first object.and the first object must not be used anymore,because it
  in indeterminacy state.
  generally,we reset the inner pointer to NULL,hence even the destructor of
  the first object is called,"delete" a NULL pointer is legal.
  the memory points by that pointer before now is pointed by the pointer in
  second object.when the destructor of the second object is called,the memory
  will be deallocated.

in rust,for heap object,move semantics always applied when execute assignment.
if we used the object that is moved,compiler will throw error.
! this will prevent shallow copy happens on heap object.

drop() also will be called if we assign to an object which been holds a heap object.
    let mut s = String::from("old");
    s = String::from("new"); // drop() will be called to drop the String object
                             // which has literal "old".
                             // at there,a new String object is produced and
                             // bound to @s,the older will be dropped.
! this is behaves std::unique_ptr<> in C++,when we assign the smart pointer a
  new pointer,the older will be released.

deeply copy is available in rust for heap object,the common method clone() can 
handle this.
    let s1 = String::from("hello");
    let s2 = s1.clone(); // new String object is cloned from @s1,and bound to @s2

rust has special annotation called "Copy" trait,we can place on the types are 
stored on the stack.when assignment execute,rust will copy the object rather than
move it.(trivally copied)
if the type or any of its parts,has implemented the "Drop" trait,then we can not
place "Copy" trait on it.
!! some built-in simple types are Copy trait applied,such integer,char,boolean,
   and floating-point.
   for tuple,it is Copy trait applied if and only if all its types are Copy trait
   applied.

Ownership and Functions >
    passing variable to a function will move or copy.
    for Copy trait type,the passing will do object copy.
    for no Copy trait type,the passing will do object move.
        fn the_func(x: i32) {
        }

        let x = 3;
        the_func(x); // copy

        fn take_ownership(s: String) {
        } // parameter @s will be dropped when it goes out of function scope.

        let s = String::from("move");
        take_ownership(s); // move,and local @s is no longer valid.

Return Values and Scope >
    returning values can also transfer ownership.
        fn transfer_ownership() -> String {
            let s = String::from("move");
            s
        }

        let s = transfer_ownership();

                                      // takes ownership
        fn transfer_ownership_giveback(cur_owner: String) -> String {
            cur_owner // return ownership
        }

        let s = String::from("owner");
        let s1 = transfer_ownership_giveback(s); // @s is moved
        // @s1 takes ownership from the function,that is
           the @s's String object.

References and Borrowing >
    symbol '&' prefixes on an object can makeup a reference to that object.
    when we has a function receives a parameter is associated with heap object,
    pass argument to it will cause move semantics.for let the argument still
    valid after function calling finished,we need to return the ownership from
    the function.if we want to return another value of different type,then we
    can not return the ownership.
    for deal with this,we can pass a reference to the argument to that function.
    after the function calling is finished,the argument still valid.
        fn calculate_length(str: &String) -> usize {
            str.len()       //   ^type is String reference.
        }                   // then we can use the object without need to take
                            // ownership.

        let s = String::from("Hello");
        let len: usize = calculate_length(&s);
        // @s still valid,and no heap object is dropped.
    ! reference has no ownership.

    in rust,the action of creating a reference is called "borrowing".
    because we borrowed it,so we has no ownership,thus we can not modify it.
    but there is a way to let us modify the borrowed thing.
    we can makeup a multable reference,this require the original object also is
    mutable.
        fn add_one(a: &mut i32) -> i32 {
            *a += 1; // ^mutable references
            *a
        } // behaves like to prefix-increment

        let mut x = 5;
        let y = add_one(&mut x); // create mutable reference,and pass it.
    ! no keyword "mut",will create immutable reference by default,even the original
      is mutable.
    ! '*' is dereference operator,it can be used for reference,to get the orignal
      value of the target the reference refers to.
          let mut x = 0;
          let ref_x = &x; // makeup a reference,@ref_x is type of reference
          let y = *ref_x; // dereference

      ! different from C++ reference,in rust,reference is more similar
        to a C++ pointer rather than the C++ reference.

    if we have a mutable reference to the original target,then we can not create
    any other reference to that target,whatever it is immutable reference or
    mutable reference. // conversely is the same.
        let mut x = 0;
        let m_ref = &mut x; // OK
        let imm_ref = &x;   // ERROR,because there been a mutable reference to @x
        let m_ref1 = &mut x; // ERROR,same reason

        let y = 0;
        let imm_ref_y = &y; // OK
        let imm_ref1_y = &y; // OK
    ! we can not borrow the object as mutable more than once at a time.
      we can only create a new mutable reference until the last one is
      goes out scope.(lifetime is end)
      this restrict can prevent data race at compile time.
      when we got a mutable reference,no one can got an immutable reference,it
      can only do this after this mutable reference is goes out of scope;and as
      same as the conversely.(immutable _references_ go out of scope)

    ! scope of reference is different from variable's scope.for a reference,its
      lifetime is start from where it has declared,and continue to the last time
      the reference is used,such scopes,can not overlap.
          let x = 0;

          // scope starting of @imm_ref_x.
          let imm_ref_x = &x;                   
          ...
          let y = *imm_ref_x; // use the immutable reference,the last usage.
          // scope ending of @imm_ref_x.

          // scope starting of @m_ref_x.
          let m_ref_x = &mut x; // OK
          ...
          let z = *m_ref_x; // last usage of the mutable reference.
          // scope ending of @m_ref_x.

          let imm_ref1_x = &x; // OK

          // such these scopes are can be known at compile time.

Dangline References >
    dangline references are easily to cause error about used after freed,
    or been given to someone.

    in rust,the compiler guarantees that references will never be dangling
    references.if we have a reference to some data,the compiler will ensure
    the data will not go out of scope before the reference to the data does.
    in other word,the data will not be dropped before its reference go out
    of scope.
        fn make_dangle() -> &String {
            let s = String::from("dangle");
            &s  // compiler will throws error
        }
    for prevent this,we can return object via move semantics to instead
    return reference.    // return ownership

The rules of references >
    at any given time,we can have either one mutable reference or any number of
    immutable references.
    references must always be valid.

The Slice Type >
    slice let us reference a contiguous sequence of elements in a collection.
    a slice is a kind of reference,so it does not have ownership.
    that is,we can reference to a part of the sequence instead to reference 
    the entire.
        let s = String::from("Hello, world");
                             #^index 0

                    // range-syntax,default is half-open.
        let hello = &s[0..5]; // slice type,@hello refers to @s,
                              // start from index 0,end at index 5.
                              // index range is [0, 5).
                              // and index [0, 4] => "Hello".
        let world = &s[7..12]; // same as @hello,refers to "world".
                               // index range is [0, 12).
    when producing slice type object,the rust range syntax implies start index is 0,
    end index is the sequence ending more than one.so we can do
        let hello = &s[..5];
        let world = &s[7..];

        ! we cant omit the range boundary in the for-cycle when using range syntax.
    if we want a slice refers to entire sequence,we can omit start and end as well.
        let entire = &s[..];
    the type descriptor for slice type reference to string is "&str".
        fn first_work(s: &String) -> &str {
            ...
            &s[..]  // entire,but we also can slice a part,in other branch.
        }
    because slice is a reference,if the original target becomes invalid before
    the last usage of this reference,compiler will throw error.so we can ensure
    the slice always is valid unitl its last usage.
    ! slice type is reference,thus it also following the rule about creating
      immutable reference and mutable reference at same time.

    in rust,the string literal implies a slice type.
        let s = "hello"; // @s is &str,the slice type.
    slice type can also be used as function parameter's type.
        fn recv_slice(s: &str) -> &str {
            ...
        }

    rust also provides array slice,and other slices.for array slice,its type
    is &[<data-type>].
        let x = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
        let array_slice = &x[0..4]; // slice [0, 4) => [0, 3]
                                    // contains: 0, 1, 2, 3
                                    // type of @array_slice is &[i32].

    ! the reason compile throw an error when original becomes invalid before
      last use of slice is
          for invalidate the original target,drop() need a mutable reference
          to it.
          and slice is reference,it following the rule about reference creating.

Rust Structure :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

keyword "struct" can be used to define a structure.
    struct TheStruct {
        @member-name: <type>,
        ...
    }
for instantiate a structure,we can do this same as declare a variable and init it.
    let obj: TheStruct = TheStruct {
        @member-name: <initializer>,
        ...
    }; // initializing order regardless.

    let obj = TheStruct {
        @member-name: <initializer>,
        ...
    };

operator "." can be used on structure object to access its member.
    obj.@member-name = ...; // assignment
    obj.@member-name += ...; // obj.@member-name = obj.@member-name + ...
    // like the member access operator in C and C++.
note that,if we want to modify a member of a structure,then this structure must
be _entire_ mutable. // rust does not support mutable on certain member.

we can return a new structure object from a function.
    fn ret_structure() -> TheStruct {
        TheStruct {
            @member-name: <initializer>,
            ...
        }
    }

rust support init shorthand syntax,when we has a object whose name is same as 
the structure member's name,and we want use the object to initialize that member.
we can omit initializer of that member.
    let member-name = 5;
    let obj = TheStruct {
        member-name,
        ...
    };

if we want to create another object has the same type as previous object,we can
use the previous object's member to initialize this new object.
    let obj = TheStruct {
        ...
    };

    let obj1 = TheStruct {
        @member-name: obj.@member-name,
        ...
    };
follow this way,we need to write a lot of things,thus rust does support the
update syntax.
    let obj = TheStruct {
        ...
    };

    let obj1 = TheStruct {
        @member1-name: <initializer>,
        ..obj // this is the update syntax.
    };
where ".." means the remain fields of @obj1 will initialized from @obj's members.
!! rust update syntax works like the "=" assignment,that means it will apply
   move semantics on the assignment.for on stack object,copy semantics will be
   applied.

we also can define tuple struct,such structure has no detail of member definitions.
    struct TupleStruct(<type1>, <type2>, ...);
    let t = TupleStruct(<initializer1>, ...);
this is useful when member name is less importance,and we want to give a meaningful
name to a tuple,to distinguish from other tuples.

rust does support unit-like struct,such struct is useful to implement a trait for
other types.
    struct UnitLikeStruct;  // definition
    let obj = UnitLikeStruct; // declare

we can also specify the member's type of a struct is a reference,which will refers
to another data.
but for do this,we need to specify the use of lifetimes.
    struct RefStruct {
        ref1: &<lifetime specifier> i32,
        ...
    }
lifetimes ensure that the data referenced by a struct is valid for as long as
the struct is.

generally,we can not println!() a struct object,because maybe the structure has
not implemented method "std::fmt::Display".
we can force to print the structure's detail by apply the outer attribute
"#[derive(Debug)]".
    #[derive(Debug)]
    struct TheStruct {
        one: i32,
        two: i32,
    }

    let obj = TheStruct {
        one: 1,
        two: 2,
    };

    println!("@obj is {obj:?}"); // debugging print.
! the attribute "#[derive(Debug)]" only effects the next most neared definition.
  so we need
      #[derive(Debug)]
      struct TheStruct {
          ...
      } // TheStruct is Debug derived.
  we can do this but
      #[derive(Debug)]
      struct NewTuple(u32, u32, u32); // NewTuple is Debug derived.

      // now TheStruct has no Debug attribute derived.
      struct TheStruct {
          ...
      }    

another way is use the "dbg!" macro,which takes ownership of an expression,
prints the file and line number of where that "dbg!" macro call occurs.
! println!() takes a reference.
    #[derive(Debug)]
    ...
    let obj = TheStruct {
        one: dbg!(1),
        two: dbg!(2),
    };

a language can be object-oriented must need to support member method,such method
describes what actions we can take on the object.
in C
    struct obj {
            int x;
            void (*modify_x)(struct obj* obj, int new_value);
    };

    void obj_modify_x(int new_value)
    {
            obj->x = new_value;
    }

in C++
    struct obj {
      void modifyX(int v)
      {
        x_ = v;
      }

      int x_;
    }

rust also support member method,but different from C and C++,it use the keyword
"impl" to define member methods for a certain structure outside to the definition
of this structure.  #^also called "associated function".
    struct TheStruct {
        x: i32,
    }

    impl TheStruct {
        fn modify_x(&mut self, v: i32) {
            self.x = v;
        }

        // &self is short of "self: &self".
        // & -> we borrow ownership.
        // no '&' means member method takes ownership,
        // this is the rare case.
        fn return_x(&self) -> i32 {
            self.x
        }
    }
where "self" works like the "this" pointer in C++ class methods.it refers to the
object entity on which this method is called.
the "self" type of an implementation is the type of the structure this implementation
associated with.
and member method _must_ has the first parameter named "self".
we need to ensure the name of implementation must be the same as the name of the
structure this implementation wants associate with.
method's name can be same as the member name of the structure,similar to C++.

invoke member method
    let obj = TheStruct {
        x: 5,
    };

    // for return_x() &obj will be passed
    println!("@obj.x is {}.", obj.return_x());
    obj.modify_x(10); // for modify_x() &mut obj will be passed
    println!("@obj.x is {}.", obj.return_x());

    // @obj is called the receiver of the member method.
    // rust adds '&' '&mut' or '*' to the object for matches the
    // signature of member method.
    // thi is called "automatically referencing and dereferencing".

we can let the associated function to return a new object,such method is called
"new method",and we can call to such method do not need an object entity,but
instead,we need to call it through namespace operator "::".
such associated method do not requires the first parameter is "self".
    impl TheStruct {
        fn new(x: i32) -> Self {
            Self {
                x,
            }
        }
    }

    let new_obj = TheStruct::new(20);
where "Self" is different from "self","Self" is a keyword,it represents the type
this "impl" associated with.

rust allows separate member methods into several "impl" definitions,this is very
similar to the namespace definition in C++.
    impl TheStruct {
        fn return_x(&self) -> i32 {
            self.x
        }
    }

    impl TheStruct {
        fn modify_x(&mut self, v: i32) {
            self.x = v;
        }
    }

Enums and Pattern Matching :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

enumeration can be used to represent a type has several possible variants,and
an object has such type can only one of the possible variants at same time.
    enum <enumeration-name> {
        <enumerator>,
        ...
    }
we usually name the @enumerator with upper case characters,like a constant.
    enum ColorEnum {               //^OK,this is the convention in C and C++.
        RED,
        BLUE,
        BLACK,
        ...
    }
    let current_color = ColorEnum::RED; // create enumeration instance.
generally,program can use the enumeration object as the identifier to determine
what action should be taken for specified resource.
    fn handle_red(c: ColorEnum) {

    }

    fn handle_blue(c: ColorEnum) {

    }

    ...

    fn handle_color(c: ColorEnum) {
        if c == ColorEnum::RED {
            handle_red(c);
        } else if c == ColorEnum::BLUE {
            handle_blue(c);
        }
        ...
    }
we usually let the resource structure to contains an enumeration object to
identify what current resource is for the same resource type.such use it to
identify the version information.
rust does support enumerator has other type than integer.
    enum ColorEnum {
        RED(u8, u8, u8),
        BLUE(u8, u8, u8),
        ...
    }
    // we use the tuple to store the color numbers.

    let red = ColorEnum::RED(255, 0, 0);
                            #^invoke constructor,automatically created.
and rust,does not requires the types of each enumerator must be the same.
    enum ErrorEnum {
        ERROR_GENERAL(u8),
        ERROR_FATAL(u8, String),
    }
    let error_result = ErrorEnum::ERROR_FATAL(-32, String::from("fatal error"));

rust allows we to define method implementations for an enumeration type.as same
as the structure,keyword "impl" is needed.
    impl ErroEnum {
        fn handle_fatal_error(&mut self) {
            ...
        }
    }
    let mut error_result=ErrorEnum::ERROR_FATAL(-32, String::from("fatal"));
    error_result.handle_fatal();

rust standard library provides a pre-defined enumeration type,named "Option".
"Option" can be used to describe a value could be something or it could be nothing.
for represent it,tradinal language such C and C++ use NULL value to descripbes
the object current is invalid.
when we try to use a NULL object as a not-null object,this usually cause the
fatal error at runtime.compiler would not tell us the bad using of NULL object.
such problem is "assuming that something is not null when it actually is null.".
by use "Option",we can not process some actions on it when it is invalid,if we
did,compiler will throw error.
    enum Option<T> {
        None,
        Some(T),
    } // generic in rust.
    let valid_Option = Option<i32>::Some(10);
    let invalid_Option = Option<i32>::None;

    // if we used @invalid_Option eventually because we have forgot
    // it has not been initialized,compiler will tell us this error.
! we can use Option directly from std without "::".
! if we want to match Option<T> object,we can just list the pattern
      None
      Some(@e)
  to instead list the pattern in the style
      Option::<T>::None
      Option::<T>::Some(@e)
  note that,if we list the pattern in the style "Option<T>::None",
  rustc will throw error.because generics need specify lifetime.

The "match" Control Flow Construct >
    keyword "match" is used specify a match-expression.
        match @v {
            @pattern => @action,
            ...
        }
    where @v usually is an object will be compared with the patterns,and
    @pattern can be made up of literal values,variable names,wildcards,etc.
    if the first matched pattern occurs,the @action(code block) corresponds to that
    pattern will be executed.
    @action can be compound statement.
    ! similar to the switch statement in C and C++.

    match-expression supports variable binding between match value's parts and match pattern arm.                                            
                                                                    #^usually is the inner
        enum Enum {
            ENUM(String),
        }
        match e {
            Enum::ENUM(s) => {
                // in this compound statement,@s is bound to the
                // String object which is inside the enumerator ENUM.
            }
        }

        let e = Enum::ENUM(String::from("binding"));
                           #^@s will be bound to this object.
    we can combine Option<T> with the match-expression,manipulate the option object
    if and only if it is not None.
        let x = Option<i32>::Some(10);
        match x {
            None => None,
            Some(v) => println!("x is {v}"),
        }

        fn return_option(x: Option<i32>) -> Option<i32> {
            match x {
                None => None,
                Some(v) => Some(v + 2),
            }
        }   
    ! for the type T in Some(T),if Copy trait has implemented,the match binding
      will use copy instead move.
      if we want to borrow the value whose type has no Copy trait implemented,we
      can invoke as_ref() member method on the Option<> object,or use the "ref"
      keyword in pattern matching.
          match x {
              None => ... ,
              Some(ref v) => ... ,  // @v is a reference to the exact value.
          }

    result of match-expression is the result of that matched arm's.

    usually,we need list all possible patterns for the match-expression corresponding
    to that match value.
    but,because match pattern supports wildcards,so we can take a predefined action
    for all other pattern.(catch-all arm)
        match v {
            ...
            other => @action,
        } // if @v is ENUM(String),@other is bound to the String object.

        match v {
            ...
            _ => @action,
        }
    where @other is the catch-all pattern,when this pattern is matched,@other
    will be bound to the inner of @v.
    '_' is placeholder,it similar to @other,but without variable binding.
    ! a null tuple () can be used as the result of match-expression.
    ! the catch-all arm must be the last one of match-expression.
    ! catch-all => "default:" branch of switch statement in C and C++.

    we can combine keyword "match" and keyword "let" to use match-expression when
    declaring a variable.
        let var = match @v {
            @pattern1 => @value1,
            @pattern2 => @value2,
            ...
        };
    but,we must ensure the types of values for those patterns are the same type.
    this is because rustc need to knows what is type of @var is at compile time.
    if @value1 is i32,then it expects @value2 also is i32,and so on.

"if let" and "let...else" >
    "if let" syntax can let us combine "if" and "let" to handle values that match
    one pattern while ignore the rest.
        let e = Enum::ENUM(String::from("if let"));

        //     |<-------------->| => order between them can not be swapped.
        //     |                |    local variable must after
        //     |                |    "let" keyword's operand.
        //     V                V
        if let Enum::ENUM(s) =  e {
            // @s is bound to the String object.
        }
        // of course,we can also use two arms match-expression to implement this.
    an "else" branch can follow the "if let",such branch similar to the placeholder
    pattern in match-expression.
    the compound statement of "if let" can contains another "if..else" statement,
    for handle further case,and in that branch,part binding been happened.

    "if let" can be used with the "let" keyword to declare an object.
        let x = if let ... ;
    but a more concise version is exist.
        let x = Enum::ENUM(String::from("let...else"));
        let Enum::ENUM(s) = x else {
            ...
        };
    the example is,if @x matched the pattern,declare an object named @s,bind to
    the inner string object of @x;otherwise,execute the else branch.

Packages,Crates,and Modules :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Packages => a cargo feature that lets us build,test,and share crates.
Crates => a tree of modules that produces a library or executable.
Modules and use => let us control the organization,scope,and privacy of paths.
Paths => a way of naming an item,such as a struct,function,or module.

a crate is the smallest amount of code that the rust compiler considers at a time.
a crate has one of the two form,executable or library.
the crate root is a source file that the rustc starts from and makes up the root
module of the crate.

a package is a bundle of one or more crates that provides a set of functionality.
a package contains a "Cargo.toml" file,it describes how to build those crates.
a package can contains a lot of binary crates,but at most only one library crate.
a package must contains at least one crate.
! convetion: src/main.rs of project directory is the crate root of a binary
             crate with the same name as the package.
             if only src/lib.rs is exist,then this file is the library crate root.
a package can has multiple binary crates by placing files in src/bin,each file
will be a separate binary crate.

keyword "mod" can be used to declares a module,and keyword "pub" apply on a
module can let the module become public,if no "pub" keyword,"mod" will declare
a private module by default.
    mod new_module; // private
    
    pub mod new_module; // public
"mod" keyword tell rustc to include the code of that module into current file,
"pub" means the module is global visible.
// include means,the module exists and is part of this crate.

rustc's work >
    start from the crate root
        main.rs
    declaring modules
        // mod <module-name>;

        checks whether the "crate root" has declaring modules.
        lookup module's code in
            in main.rs
            src/<module-name>.rs
            src/<module-name>/mod.rs
    declaring submodules
        checks whether the module has submodules.
        lookup submodule's code in
            parent module's source file
            src/<parent-module-name>/<submodule-name>.rs
            src/<parent-module-name/<submodule-name>/mod.rs
    paths to code in modules
        once a module is part of the crate,we can refer to code
        in that module from anywhere else in that same crate,
        as long as the privacy rules allow.
    private VS. public
        code within a module is private from its parent modules
        by default.
        if "pub" keyword is given,then the module is public.
    the "use" keyword
        within a scope,the "use" keyword creates shortcuts to items
        to reduce repetition of long paths.

we can group related code in modules,this also rely on the "mod" keyword.
    mod <module-name> {
        mod <submodule-name> {
            ...
        }
        ...
    } // module definition
modules can also hold definitions for other items,such as structs,enums,constants,
traits,and functions.
this is similar to C++ namespace.as the same,if the items in a module is not global
visible,then we need to use operator "::" to access them.
a path can take two forms >
    1> an absolute path is the full path starting from a crate root.
       for external crate,path begins with the crate name.
       for current crate,path begins with the literal "crate".
    2> a relative path starts from the current module and use "self","super",
       or an identifier in the current module.
path identifiers in the path is separated by "::".
    mod module_x {
        mod submodule_x {
            fn func() { }
        }
    }

    // there "pub" is used to expose the public API.
    pub fn pub_func() {
        crate::module_x::submodule_x::func(); // absolute path
    
        module_x::submodule_x::func(); // relative path
    }
    // because submodule_x is private module,thus rustc will throw error
    // if we just compile the example.

we can expose paths with the "pub" keyword.
    module module_x {
        pub mod submodule_x {
            fn func() { }
        }
    }
now the submodule submodule_x becomes public,but this is not enough.the submodule
becomes public,the contents in the submodule still private.
so,we need to expose the private contents,too.
    module module_x {
        pub mod submodule_x {
            pub fn func() { } // expose func() as public,
                              // no"pub" keyword,the function
                              // is private item by default.
        }
    }

we can construct relative paths that begin in the parent module,rather than the
current module or the crate root,by using "super" at the start of path.
    mod module_x {
        fn func() {}
        mod submodule_x {
            fn func() {
                internal_func();
                super::func();
            }

            fn internal_func() { }
        }
    }

we also can make the structs and the enums public,by use "pub" keyword.
if we want the structure become public,then we can
    mod module_x {
        pub struct X {
            field1: i32,
            field2: u32,
        }

        impl X {
            pub fn access_field1(&self) -> i32 {
                self.field1
            }
        }
    }
the structure and the interface become public,they can be accessed by external
crate.but we can not access to the fields directly,if we want to allow that,
need to apply "pub" on the fields.
    mod module_x {
        pub struct X {
            pub field1: i32, // public field
            field2: u32, // private field
        }
    }
! in a binary crate,we might define structure in the global scope.in that case,
  we can access to the field directly,but if we put them into module,private will
  be default behavior.
public enum as same as the structure,except we usually do not apply "pub" on the
enumerators.

keyword "use" can be used to bring paths into scope,like the "using" keyword in
C++.
    use crate::module_x::X;
    // now the structure X is visible directly in current scope.
    // same as we did to bring std::string to main scope.

    use crate::module_x::submodule_x;
      //^current crate,absolute path.

    mod module_y {
        fn func() {
            submodule_x::func(); // ERROR
            super::submodule_x::fun(); // OK
        }
    }
    // the reason is,when we define a module,the name resolve default is inside
    // current module.if we want to access parent scope,then need the relative
    // path identifer to specify that.
    // or we can use the "use crate::module_x::submodule_x::func;" at the
    // top scope,then we can invoke the func() directly without "super"
    // identifier.

keyword "as" can be used together with "use" to alias a type.
    use std::io::Result as IoResult;
there "IoResult" is the new name of the type std::io::Result in current crate.
! in C and C++,"typedef" and "using" can do the same.

when we bring a name into scope with the "use",the name is private to the scope
into which we imported it.but we can re-export the name from this scope,"pub"
can does this.
    pub use crate::module_x::submodule_x::func;
    // re-export,now func() in that module can be accessed by external code.

we can use external packages,section "dependencies" of the file "Cargo.toml" is
used to specify external packages.if we specified one and our code has used the
parts of external packages,then cargo would automatically download it during
compile time.
    // Cargo.toml
    [dependencies]
    rand = "0.8.5"

    // main.rs
    use rand::Rng;

we can combine several same prefix paths into one "use".
    use std::cmp::Ordering;
    use std::io;

    =>

    use std::{cmp::Ordering, io};
special name "self" can be used in the combinition to use the module itself.
    use std::io;
    use std::io::Write;

    =>

    use std::io{self, Write};

wildcards '*' can be used in "use" statement,it will brings all public items from
that module into current scope.
    use std::collections::*;

similar to C++,when we have several modules in our rust program,we can separate
them into different files.
! in C++,we separate namespace definitions into different files.
keyword "mod" can be used to declare a module at current scope.
// but private module can not be declared by other crate through "mod".
because rustc lookup the module from the file has the same module name,thus,
usually one source file can only has one main module.
    // module_x.rs
    pub mod module_y {
        pub fn func() { }
    }

    // lib.rs
    mod module_x;
    pub use crate::module_x::module_y::func;
! if we separate modules into different files,the file can also be a private module implicitly.
      // module_x.rs
      pub fn func() { }
  there,the file "module_x.rs" will corresponds to a module named "module_x",and its
  contents just a public function named @func.
  then we can import it into main.rs
      mod module_x;
      use crate::module_x::func;

      fn main() {
          func();
      }

  another method is,touch a file named "module_x.rs".
      // src/module_x.rs
      pub mod module_y;
  create a directory named "module_x",and touch a file named "module_y.rs".
      // src/module_x/module_y.rs
      pub fn func() { }
  and we can invoke the function in main.rs
      // src/main.rs
      mod module_x;
      use crate::module_x::module_y::func;

! usually,a project may has its own library functions need by itself.
  we should separate these functions into different module,and bring them
  into the library file "lib.rs".
  we can refer to these APIs in a binary crate through the "use" keyword.
      use <project-name>::<component-name>;
  where @project-name corresponds to the library crate "lib.rs",we refer
  to library through project's name.

Common Collections :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

collections is the useful data structures inclued in rust standard library.
such data structure can contain multiple values,and the element in the collection
is stored on the heap.
! similar to C++ container.
    
collection Vec<T> >
    a vector,can store more than one value in a single data structure,each element
    in the collection is next to each other in memory,and vector can only holds
    one type of element.rust vector is defined in module "std::Vec".
        let iv: Vec<i32> = Vec::new(); // empty collection with certain type.

        let iv1 = vec![1, 2, 3]; // type is auto deduced to i32,integer default.
                //^initilization
    member method push() can be used to update a vector object.
        iv.push(1);
        iv.push(2);
        iv.push(3);
        // @iv must be mutable.
    and push() method will borrow the "self" in mutable,this means,if we
    have an immutable reference to an element in this collection,before
    leave the immutable scope,push() method would not work. 
        let rfirst: &i32 = &iv[0]; // immutable reference.
        v.push(4); // need mutable borrow @iv.
        // this is because add new element at the end will cause re-allocation,
        // we might need to copy the old elements into the new space,if there
        // is not enough room to store this new element.
        // after copying,the old memory space will be deallocated,thus @rfirst
        // points a invalid element.
    the subscript operator [] can be applied on a vector to access the element.
        iv[0]
        iv[1]
        ...
    and there also a member method get() can be used to access the element.
    but different from [],get() method returns a value is type of Option<&T>.
        let x = iv.get(0); // Option<&i32>
    if we access an element through [] outside to the vector's range,then a
    runtime panic will happens,and program will crash.
    for get() method,the special value "None" will be returned,no panic happens.
    ! rustc can not detect [@bad_area] error because vector can dynamically grow
      or shrink at runtime.
    ! we can use operator '&' on vector's get() method to get the reference to
      that Option<T> object instead to copy a new Option<T>.
          &iv.get(0)

    vector support for-cycle to iterate each element in the collection.
        for i in &iv {
            ...
        } // borrow @iv with immutable

        for mi in &mut iv {
            ...
        } // borrow @iv with mutable
    a vector object will be destructed(dropped) when it goes out to its scope,
    this will also drops all elements in it.

    because vector can only holds one type,but this limitation is not enforced
    onto the type it holding.
    so if we want to store several types,we can use structure or enumeration,and
    let vector to holds the struct type or enum type.
    in this case,r/w method of vector will return the object that is type of the
    compound type.
        enum ENUM {
            Int(i32),
            Float(f32),
            Text(String),
        }

        let mut v: Vec<ENUM> = vector::new();
        v.push(ENUM::Int(2));
        v.push(ENUM::Float(3.2));
        v.push(ENUM::Text(String::from("text")));

collection String >
    rust strings are implemented as a collection of bytes,with some methods
    to provide useful functionality when those bytes are interpreted as text.

    we can conver &str to a String object,through the to_string() method of the
    &str.
        let s = "the string";
        let sstr = s.to_string();

        let sstr1 = "the string".to_string(); // OK
    method from() of String means construct a String object from the given text.
    rust strings are UTF-8 encoded.

    method push_str() can be used to update the String object,it effect is append
    the text passed to it at the end of it receiver -- the String object.
        let mut hstr = String::from("Hello");
        let s = " world";
        hstr.push_str(s);

        hstr.push_str(" world"); // OK
    and of course,just push one character to the String object also permitted,
    member method push() is used to do this.
        hstr.push('x');
    except member method push_str(),the operator '+' can be used to combine
    two strings.
        let s1 = String::from("Hello ");
        let s2 = String::from("world!");
        let s3 = s1 + &s2; // the operands' order is important.
    in this expression,the operator '+' actually uses the method add() to
    combine strings,and its prototype may like this
        fn add(self, s: &str) -> String { ... }
    @s2 has prefixed '&' that is because we can only add a string slice to a 
    String object.
    ! rust coerce &String argument into a &str.
          &s2 => &s2[..]

    rust provides "format!" macro,it allows we to combine strings in more
    complicated ways.
        let s1 = String::from("YYYY");
        let s2 = String::from("MM");
        let s3 = String::from("DD");
        let time_string = format!("{s1}-{s2}-{s3}"); // result is String object
        // @time_string => "YYYY-MM-DD"
    ! format!() macro does not take ownership of strings,it uses references of
      them.

    String does not support subscript operation,because it support all UTF-8
    encoded characters,different string has different length than the length of
    that literal string.besides this,subscript operation on string would returns
    a byte value,not a character.and,rust would have to walk through the
    contents from the beginning to the index([@idx]) to determine how many
    valid characters there were,but operator [] expects O(1) time complexity,
    in rust,this is not possible.

    rust provides different ways of interpreting the raw string data that computers
    store so that each program can choose the interpretation it needs,no matter 
    what human language the data is in.
    
    we can use &@String-obj[@range] to get a slice object,but we must specify
    the valid range,in other word,the range can not begins at the middle of
    a character's byte,and can not ends at the middle of a character's byte.
    for example,if the character is 2 bytes,then the start and the end of range
    must be multiple of 2.
        [0..2], [0..4], ... // OK
        [0..1], [0..3], ... // ERROR,runtime panic

    we can iterate each character in a string through for-cycle.
    the best way is to explicit the characters or bytes that we want to iterate.
                 // to characters
        for c in "text".chars() {
            ...
        }

                       // to bytes
        for b in "text".bytes() {
            ...
        }

        // "text" is &str type.

collection Hash Maps >
    the type HashMap<K, V> stores a mapping of keys of type K to values of type V
    using a "hashing function",the function determines how it places these keys
    and values into memory.(so HashMap<> is not ordered)
    for a HashMap,we can address the value through specified key;similar to the
    index on vector.

    HashMap is defined in standard library module "collections".
        use std::collections::HashMap; // use module

        let mut map: HashMap<u32, String> = HashMap::new();
        map.insert(0, String::from("Zero"));
        map.insert(1, String::from("One"));
    all of the keys have the same type,all of the values have the same type.

    member method get() can be used access element in HashMap,it requires the
    key to find out corresponding value,and it will returns an Option<&V> object.
    we can invoke method copied() to let the Option object wraps ownership rather
    than reference.
    method unwrap_or() can be used to handle the case no such key entry is exist
    in this collection.
        let x = map.get(0).copied().unwrap_or(String::from("no such entry"));
        // if no such entry,the String object from "no such entry" will be returned.

    rust supports for-cycle on HashMap to iterate its elements.
        // @key bind to current mapping's key
        // @value bind to current mapping's value
        for (key, value) in &map {
            ...
        }

    for types that implemented Copy trait,the object will be copied into HashMap,
    but for the heap based object,move semantics will be applied,that means the
    HashMap become the owner of that object.
    HashMap can stores the references to heap objects,in this case,no move will
    happens,but the original object must be valid for at least as long as the 
    HashMap is valid.

    the new value of the same key been exist into HashMap will replace the old
    value,if we insert the same key with different value more than once.
        map.insert(0, String::from("one"));
        map.insert(0, String::from("new one")); // "new one" replace "one".
    the old value will be auto dropped.

    member method entry() can be used to check whether the given key does exist
    in the HashMap.it returns an object is type of Entry enum,which represents
    a value that might or might not exist.
    because HashMap implemented with unique key,so we can use this method to 
    insert a new key-value pair if and only if the key is not exist.
        map.entry(0).or_insert(String::from("new one"));
    where method or_insert() will be called when Entry represents None such
    key-value,it will create a new key-value pair and insert it into HashMap.
    the key is same as the checked key.
    or_insert() returns a mutable reference to the _value_ for that Entry key if
    such key existed;otherwise,it returns a mutable reference to the new value.

    by use or_insert(),we can achieve the logic
        if there been a given key is exist in HashMap,then we update its value.
        if there no such key is exist in HashMap,then we create new pair,insert
        it into HashMap,and initialize its value.

            let ref = map.entry(0).or_insert(0);
            *ref += 1; // new value has value 1,
                       // old value increase by 1.

    the default hash function of HashMap is called "SipHash",it has most security
    but slower than other hash function.
    we can switch to another hash function by specify a hasher,
    a hasher is a type that implements the BuildHasher trait.

Error Handling :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

rust groups errors into two categories,the recoverable and the unrecoverable.

rust macro "panic!" can be used to stop execution of program when we encountered
an unrecoverable error.
program may implicitly panics,such we access the position into an array exceeded
its end;or we invoke panic!() to explicitly trigger panic.
by default,when program panics,rust will let the program print a failure message,
unwind and clean up stack,then exit.
of course,we can hand over the unwinding to operating system,when panic occurs,
aborting will instead unwinding.
for do this,we need to add "panic = 'abort'" into section "[profile]" of the 
Cargo.toml file.
    panic!("failure message"); // panic,print the panic message.
if we have set environment RUST_BACKTRACE to 1,then rust will print backtrace,
if we want to get verbose backtrace information,need to set this environment to
'full'. // backtrace need Debug symbols.

rust introduced a generic type Result<T, E>,it is enumeration type.
    enum Result<T, E> {
        Ok(T),
        Err(E),
    }
where T represents the type of the value that will be returned in a success case
within the @Ok variant,and E represents the type of the error that will be returned
in a failure case within the @Err variant.
we can use match-expression to extract the result.
    use std::fs::File;

    let file_result = File::open("./zero");
    let f = match file_result {
        Ok(the_file) => the_file,
        Err(the_error) => panic!("error: {the_error:?}"),
    };
if we wont to stop program when the file is not exist,instead,we want to create it.
then we can do 
    let f = match file_result {
        Ok(the_file) => the_file,
        Err(the_error) => match the_error.kind() {
            ErrorKind::NotFound => match File::create("./zero") {
                Ok(handle) => handle,
                Err(err) => panic!("create file failed"),
            }
            _ => panic!("unknown error"),
        },
    };

    // there E of Result is type of std::io::Error.
    // kind() is a member method of std::io::Error structure,
    // this method return a value is type of std::io::ErrorKind,
    // it has variants representing the different kinds of errors
    // that might result from an "io" operation.
    // std::io::Error provides unwrap_or_else() method to make the
    // error handling logic more concise.
    /*
     * File::open("./zero").unwrap_or_else(|error| {
     *     if error.kind() == ErrorKind::NotFound {
     *         File::create("./zero").unwrap_or_else(|error| {
     *             panic!("create file failed.");
     *         })
     *     } else {
     *         panic!("unknown error");
     *     }
     * });
     */ 
unwrap() method of Result<> can extract the object is type of T wrapped in @Ok,
but if we do not specify the error condition handling through other member
function such unwrap_or_else(),the default action is panic!().
expect() method of Result<> is different from unwrap(),it only be called if
Result<> is Err(E).this method receives a description text for the error,and
invoke panic!().

in rust,we can let the functions to propagate the error it encountered to the
caller,for do this,we need the function return Result<T, E>.
similar to C++ throw an exception.
    fn open_file(s: &str) -> Result<File, String> {
        let f = File::open(s);
        match f {
            Ok(handle) => return Result::<File, String>::Ok(handle),
            Err(err) => return Result::<File,String>::Err(
                String::from("Open file failed.")),
        }   // similar to Option<>,when we construct a generic object,
    }       // we need to specify lifetime for it.

in rust,symbol '?' can be used as a shortcut for Result<> object.
    let f = File::open(s)?;
if result is Ok,'?' is same as unwrap().
if result is Err,'?' will convert E to the current function's return type,and
return the converted object to caller.(early return)

error values that have '?' operator called on them go through the 'from' function,
defined in the 'From' trait in the standard library,which is used to convert values
from one type into another.
when the '?' operator calls the 'from' function,the error type received is converted
into the error type defined in the return type of the current function.
if we want '?' convert the error type to our custom error type,we need to give
it the implementation for the conversion to From trait,describe how to convert
standard library defined error type to our custom error type.
    impl From<io::Error> {
        fn to_our_cerror(e: io::Error) -> OUR_CERROR {
            ...
        }
    }

operator? can only be used in functions whose return type is compatible with the
value the '?' is used on,generally,the value's type is Result<> or Option<>.
// compatible: Err(E) => Result<T, E>, Some(T) => Option<T>
// for Option<T>,'?' early return None.
except the end of a statement,we can also use '?' at the middle of calling chain.
    text.lines().next()?.chars().last()
    //^&str            ^no next line,return None,otherwise continue on Some(T)

in rust,main function can returns a value is type of Result<(), E>.
// 0 or error code.
except this type,the main function may return any types that implement the
std::process::Termination trait.

! call unwrap() if we have not decided to how to handle the error.
! call expect() and document the reason,if we will think never have an Err variant.
  when error case become possible,we can change expect() to other error handling 
  resolution.
! panic! if we end up in a bad state(fatal error,unexpected behavior,etc).

Generic Types,Traits,and Lifetimes :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

generics in rust is abstract stand-ins for concrete types or other properties.
it allow us to replace specific types with a placeholder that represents multiple
types to remove code duplication.
usually,we do this rely on function calling,the generic allow us to improve this
function to handle other types than a specific type by the same way.


Generic Data Types
------------------

similar to C++,rust function can receives objects that of generic types,or
return an object is type of generic type.
    fn func<T>(x: &T) -> T {
        ...
    }
'<>' is used to tell rustc 'T' is a generic type.
when we invoke this generic function with parameters have certain types,rustc
will use the certian types to replace the generic types.if some operations in
that function is not supported by current types,rustc will throw error.
we can apply trait on the generic type,to specify the type T should support
some special operations,then we can do such operations in the function.
    fn func<T: <trait-name>>(...) { }
! because generic type T may not support to ordering,if we want to compare
  objects has type T,we need to apply the trait std::cmp::PartialOrd on the
  type T,to enable comparison.
      fn func<T: std::cmp::PartialOrd>(ary: &[T]) -> &T {
          ...
      }

structure and enumeration also support generic type.
    struct Complex<T> {
        a: T,
        b: T,
    }

    enum Option<T> {
        None,
        Some(T),
    }

    enum Result<T, E> {
        Ok(T),
        Err(E),
    }
when auto deduction happens at compile time,the first initializer's type is the
generic type T.

if we want to provide some member methods for the generic structure,we need
specify generic type for "impl" keyword,too.
    //   +-- T just after 'impl' means we are
    //   |   declaring implementation for generic type,
    //   |   in the implementation,T is a generic type.
    //   |  +-- the structure corresponds to this implementation
    //   |  |
    //   V  V  
    impl<T> Complex<T> {
        fn new() -> Complex<T> {
            Complex<T> {
                a: 0,
                b: 0,
            }
        }

        fn a(&self) -> &T {
            &self.a
        }

        fn b(&self) -> &T {
            &self.b
        }
    }
similar to C++,rust also supports generic type specialization,in implementation,
but the difference is,except the specified implementation,the specified type also
has the methods defined in the generic type implementation.
    impl Complex<f32> {
        fn do_not_call(&self) {
            panic!("EINVAL");
        }
    } // we define the additional implementation for specified type.
when the object is type of Complex<f32>,then methods in this implementation will
also be considered,so we can invoke do_not_call() on the object.
for different types,implementations may provide different methods,this is OK,
but all of them,sharing the implementation for generic type.
! generic type will not slows speed of program at runtime.
  rustc performs "monomorphization" at compile time.
  the monomorphization is the process of turning generic code
  into specific code by filling in the concrete types that are
  used when compiled.
  # static dispatch.

Defining Shared Behavior with Traits
------------------------------------

Trait => a particular characteristic that can produce a particular
         type of behaviour.
By specify traits to an object,we can define the common behaviours of objects
that have the same traits.

a trait defines the functionality a particular type _has_ and can _share_ with
other types.
a type's behavior consists of the methods we can call on that type.
    trait <trait-name> {
        fn <method>(...) -> <return_type> {
            ...
        }
    }
keyword "trait" is used to define a trait with specified name.in the definition,
it is composed by some callable object(methods),those methods describe the
behaviours of this trait,and the object has such trait need to support those
methods,then we can group the objects together through trait.it is not "is-a",
it just means they are similar things.
! for example,in C++ standard library,STL specified some traits that must be
  santisfied by the related container,then we can know the object is a STL
  container.
the above,define the default implementation for a trait.
and we also can provide the special implementation for a trait that corresponds
to specified type.
    impl <trait-name> for <type-name> {
        fn <method>(...) -> <return_type> {
            ...
        }
    }
if we want use the default implementation,just leave the 'impl' be empty as well.
actually,we still need the 'impl' 'for' to apply a trait on a given type.
    struct Complex { ... }
    trait ComplexTrait { ... }
    impl ComplexTrait for Complex { }

    let v = Complex { ... };
    v.trait_method(); // OK,ComplexTrait is applied on Complex type,thus
                      // the methods in the trait implementation should be
                      // supported by Complex type.
usually,we just specify method prototype in trait definition,and provides the
detail through 'impl' 'for' keywords.
this is because,the default implementation maybe can not access to the fields
in that compound type,such structure.
    trait <trait-name> {
        fn <method-name>(...) -> <return_type>;
    }
if we want to contruct a new object from a method of the trait's implementation,
and which object's type is same as the type of object this trait applied to,
we can let the method return 'Self' instead specify the certain type.
    trait <trait-name> {
        fn copy(&self) -> Self;
    }   
    impl <trait-name> for <my-struct> {
        fn copy(&self) -> Self {
            Self {
                ...
            }
        }
    }
when the trait method is called from a receiver,"&self" is the reference to that
object,and "Self" is the type of that object,this binding is accomplished by
rustc.

we can implement a trait on a type only if either the trait or the type,or both,
are local to current crate.
but we cant implement external traits on external types.
    ---- "orphan rule"(coherence)

traits can be used as parameters of a function.
    fn func(p: &impl <trait-name>) -> <return_type> {
        ...
    }
this function accepts any type that implements the specified trait,and in the
function,we can call methods of that trait on the parameter @p.
and we can also do this through generic type,but we need to make a bound between
the generic type T and the trait.
    fn func<T: <trait-name>>(p: &T) -> <return_type> {
        ...
    }
! usually,we prefer to the "impl Trait" syntax than bind generic type.
  the reason is,if the function need more than one parameters,we can
  specify trait contraints on each parameter.
  if all parameters use the same trait,generic type should be considered.
we can specify the function's parameter is more than one traits applied on it.
    fn func(p: &(impl <Trait> + <Trait> + ...)) -> <return_type> {
        ...
    }
generic type syntax is 
    fn func<T: <Trait> + <Trait> ...>(p: &T) -> <return_type> {
        ...
    }
if there is more than one generic types of the function,specify traits for
each generic type will let the generic type list and parameter list too long,
hence will lost readability,so rust provides keyword "where" to allow us to
specify traits for generic types at other place.
    fn func<T, U, V>(t: &T, u: &U, v: &V) -> <return_type>
    where
        T: <Trait>,
        U: <Trait>,
        V: <Trait> + <Trait> + ...,
    {
        ...
    }

trait can also be applied on the return type of a function.
    fn func() -> impl <trait-name> {
        ...
    }
func() can return an object of any type that associated with the specified traits.
but this is work only for return single type.if the function will returns one of
two types that associated with the trait,rustc will throw error.
    fn func() -> impl <trait-name> {
        if true {
            <TypeA> {
                ...
            }
        } else {
            <TypeB> {
                ...
            }
        }
    } // ERROR,even both TypeA and TypeB have the specified trait.

rust supports provide different methods for generic type that has different trait.
    struct Point<T> {
        x: T,
        y: T,
    }

    impl<T> Point<T> {
        ...
    }

    impl<T: <Trait> + <Trait> ...> Point<T> {
        // special methods for T has those traits.
    }
the trait-special methods can only be called for the generic type that has the
specified traits.

Validating References with Lifetimes
------------------------------------

rustc has a borrow checker,it handles the validation of object's lifetimes for
us,usually,we do not need to care about dangle references.
    let r;  ----------------+
    {                       |
        let x = 5; -----+   |
        r = &x;         |   |
    }              <----+   |
    println!("r is {r}"); <-+
in the example,the lifetime of @x is shorter than the lifetime of @r,if @r
borrows @x,borrow checker will compares their lifetime scopes,thus it will found
@x is not live long enough as the @r,rustc will throw error.
    
rust provides lifetime annotation syntax,it 'do not' change references lifetime,
rather describe the _relationships_ of the lifetimes of multiple references to
each other without affecting the lifetimes.(generic lifetime parameter)
    &i32        // reference to i32
    &'a i32     // reference to i32 with an explicit lifetime
    &'a mut i32 // mutable reference to i32 with an explicit lifetime

    // &'<character> <refer-type>
    //  |<-------->| => lifetime annotation
we can use lifetime annotation in function's signature.
    //      +--> generic lifetime parameter
    //      |
    fn func<'a>(x: &'a i32, y: &'a i32) -> &'a i32 {
        ...
    } // the return value will be valid as long as both parameters are valid.
      // this function does not need to know exactly how long its parameters will
      // live,only that some scope can be substituted for "'a" that will
      // satisfy this signature.
if we specify the explicit lifetime for the references,rustc may throw error.
    fn func(x: &i32, y: &i32) -> &i32 {
        if x > y {
            x
        } else {
            y
        }
    } // rustc dont know which reference will be returnted at runtime,
      // but it need to knows the lifetimes of parameters in order to
      // invoke drop() at the appropriate time.
when generic lifetime parameter is interpreted by rustc,it is consists to the
scope that is equal to the smaller one.(the lifetimes of parameters can overlap)
! if one of function's parameters is a reference,and itdoes not have any
  relationship with the lifetime of others(include return value),it does
  not need a generic lifetime parameter to associated with.
      fn func<'a>(x: &'a i32, y: i32) -> &'a i32 {
          x
      } // @y unused.

we can use generic lifetime parameter in a structure definition for the member
of that structure is a reference.
    struct Ref<'a> {
        r: &'a i32,
    } // this annotation means an instance of Ref can not outlive the reference
      // it holds in its @r member.
and we can also use generic lifetime parameter for methods.
    impl<'a> Ref<'a> {
        fn get(&self) -> &i32 {
            self.r
        }
    }

lifetimes on function or method parameters are called "input lifetimes",and 
lifetimes on return values are called "output lifetimes".

lifetime elision rules >
    1> compiler assigns a lifetime parameter to each parameter that is a
       reference.
    2> if there is exactly one input lifetime parameter,that lifetime is
       assigned to all output lifetime parameters.
    3> if there are multiple input lifetime parameters,but one of them is
       "&self" or "&mut self" because this is a method,the lifetime of "self"
       is assigned to all output lifetime parameters.

    these rules only be considered by compiler.
        
there is a special lifetime annotation,it is "'static",it denotes that the
affected reference can live for the entire duration of the program.
    let str_ref: &'static str = "static str";

we can combine generic lifetime parameter and generic type,in both structure
definition and function definition.
    struct Ref<'a, T> {
        r: &'a T,
    }
    impl<'a, T> Ref<'a, T> {
        fn get(&self) -> &T {
            self.r
        } // rule3
    }

    fn func<'a, T>(ref: &'a T) -> &'a T
    where
        T: <Trait>,
    {
        ...
    }
when we need to explicitly specify the concrete type for generic type to a
structure at declaring,we can omit "'a".
    let x = 10;
    let x_ref = Ref::<i32> {
        r: &x,
    };

    /* implicit type specify,auto deduced.
     *
     * let x_ref = Ref {
     *     r: &x,
     * };
     *
     */

Automated Tests :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

the BUGs of a program should be always considered,for detect them,we often need
to write some program to test our main program.rust provides some macros and
Cargo features to simplify this action.

attribute #[test]
    this attribute can be applied onto a rust function,for the functions have
    this attribute,"cargo test" will automatically builds a test program to runs
    the annotated functions,and reports the result.
    when we create a library project through Cargo,the example for how to define
    test function is automatically produced in "lib.rs".

rust provides a macro function assert_eq!(@value, @expect),this macro does assert
that @value is equal to @expect,otherwise,it will invoke panic!() and print the
reason.
another macro is assert!(@v),it similar to assert_eq!(),but it expect @v is true.
if @v is false,panic!() will be called.
! operator '!' means "NOT",can be used with boolean value.
macro assert_ne!(@v, @dont_expect),does assert @v is not equal to @dont_expect.

each of these macros can has a custom error message,as the last parameter of this
macro function.if failed to pass the test,this message will be printed,too.
    assert!(false, "error message");
the message can be a format string,same as the format string in println!(),thus,
we can pass additional arguments after that format string to replace the
placeholder "{}".
    assert!(false, "error {}", err_msg);

attribute #[should_panic]
    the function has "should panic" applied to,it will pass the test if it exactly
    panicked.
    we can add the optional "expected" parameter to the "should panic" attribute,
    to describe what is the case we should panic.
        #[should_panic(expected = "the case we expected to panic")]
    if the function who invoked panic!() with a error message contains the
    error message we expected in "should panic",the test will pass.

the rust Result<> generic type can also be used for program test,if Ok is returned,
the test is passed,otherwise,the test is not passed.
    #[test]
    fn test_it() -> Result<(), String> {
        ...
        if good {
            Ok(())
        } else {
            Err(String::from("Test failed."))
        }
    }
! in rust,'()' is unit type,and we usually use it in the function's return value,
  wrap it into Result::Ok().
  for such function,this means we just need the function's side-effect only.
  // similar to the void type in C and C++.
! by default,cargo test runs the test function in parallel mode,but we can pass it
  command line parameter "--jobs 1" to let it runs the functions consecutively,
  this is useful if the test functions depend on each other.
! by default,if a function passed test,its output would be captured by test library,
  thus its print message would not display,if it failed to pass the test,the rust
  test library would not capture its output.
  command line parameter "--show-output" can prevent the library capture output.
! we can specify the full function's name to execute single test,or specify the
  common part of functions' names to execute subset test.

attribute #[ignore]
    function has this attribute will be skipped in normal test,this is useful to
    exclude the time-consuming functions.
    if we want to test the ignored functions only,we can pass command line
    parameter "--ignored" to cargo test.

Unit Tests
----------

the convention is to create a module named "tests" in each source file to contain
the test functions,and to annotate the module with "#[cfg(test)]".

attribute #[cfg(test)]
    cfg -- configuration,tell rust the following item should only be included 
    given a certain configuration option.
    so we use this attribute on test module to tell rust to compile the code
    of the annotated module only when cargo test is executed.

Integration Tests
-----------------

the convention is to create a directory named "tests" under the project root.
in which directory,we can create some test file.(no number limitation)
in the test file,we should define some functions annotated "#[test]",and let them
call to the library APIs.when we execute "cargo test",rust will looks into the
directory to find test files,and for each of them,compile it to an individual
crate,next runs the binary crate to see if the test is OK.

! command line parameter "--test" can be used with a specified test file to tell
  cargo test all functions in that file.
  of course,function name for certain integeration function test is available.
! if there is some helpers will be called from multiple test files,we should put
  them into the "tests/common/mod.rs",instead to create "tests/common.rs" file.
  (this can prevent cargo treats "common.rs" as an individual crate)

Iterators and Closures :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Closures
--------

rust closures are anonymous functions,can be saved in a variable,or passed as
arguments to other functions.

the closure expression in rust
    <optional move> | <parameters> | <statement> 
where @parameters represents the parameters this closure can receives,and the
@statement can be a single statement,or a compound statement.

in the statement,we can refer to local variable of current context,and
in which,we can "move a captured value out of the closure","mutate the
captured value","neither move nor mutate the value,or capture nothing
from the local context".

how the local variable is accessed in the closure,is deduced by compiler.
if we only print(read only) the parameter,immutable borrow is OK.
    || println!("{val}")
if we need to modify the captured local variable in closure,must be mutable
borrow.
    || int_vec.push(2)
if the local variable should be moved into the closure -- the local context
give up to the lifetime maintenance,the closure should take care of this,then
move semantics will satisfy.in this case,we need specify the keyword "move"
before the closure definition.
    // this usually happens in multi-thread program.
    move || ptp.run()

for Option type,its unwrap_or_else() expects a closure that takes none of 
arguments.
    || { ... }
and for Result type,its unwrap_or_else() expects a closure that takes only one
argument.
    |ec| { ... } // @ec will be bound to the inner of Err of Result.

rust closure is similar to the lambda expression in C++,but if we want the
lambda expression returns a callable object,we need to allocate a new object.
    int another_callable(void)
    {
      return 8;
    }

    auto callable = [](void) -> auto {
      ...
      return new std::function<int(void)>(another_callable);
    };
    auto another = callable();
    auto ret = want_integer(another());
    delete another;
    // we must deallocate the callable object from callable() manually.

in rust,we can declare a closure type object,similar to the lambda expression.
    let lambda_expression = |int_ref: &i32| -> i32 {
        2 * *int_ref
    };

    ! if we mutable borrow a local variable,and the closure is declared as
      a variable,then this variable must be mutable.
          let mut FnMut_Closure = || {
              local_vec.push(...);
          };  #^mutable borrow @local_vec

    ! the checking processed by borrow checker on local captured variables,
      happens at the time to define closure.
      if we declare a variable bind to a closure,the checking will happens
      at there.
          let local_closure = || {
              ...
          };  #^borrow checking
      if we have borrowed a local variable in immutable in a closure,then
      another mutable borrow happened before the last use of this immutable
      borrow will let compiler throws error.

we can call to this closure object later,follow the syntax for function
invocation.
    let i = 2;
    let j = lambda_expression(&i);
if we omitted the type of parameter of a closure,the type will be implicitly
deduced at the "first time" this closure is used.

closure trait is how function and struct can specify what kinds of closure
they can use.
closure will automatically implement one,two or all three of "Fn" traits,in an
additive fashion,depending on how the closure's body handles the values.
    1> FnOnce trait
           apply to closure that can be called once.
    2> FnMut trait
           apply to closure that do not move captured values out of their
           body,but might mutate the captured values,can be called more 
           than once.
    3> Fn trait
           apply to closure that do not move captured values out of their
           body,and do not mutate captured values,as well as closure that
           capture nothing from their environment.
           can be called more than once without mutate environment.
for example,unwrap_or_else() member method of Option<T>
    pub fn unwrap_or_else<F>(self, f: F) -> T 
    where
        F: FnOnce() -> T
        // @F is closure type,and the trait specified that,
        // @f will be called once,takes no arguments,and need
        // to return a value is type of T.
    {
        match self {
            Some(x) => x,
            None => f(),
        }
    }
! if the action will be taken in None case do not refer/modify local context,
  use the name of a function rather than a closure,because if it is a closure,
  we need to implement a Fn trait.
      let payload = none.unwrap_or_else(Vec::new());
      // if @none is None,we get a new,empty vector.

! some examples of closure trait.
      let mut list = [
          Rectangle { width: 10, height: 1},
          Rectangle { width: 2, height: 5},
          Rectangle { width: 11, height: 2},
      ];

      // sort @list by width.
      // sort_by_key() specified FnMut trait.
      // Fn trait for this closure,can be called more than once,
      // thus meets the trait bound requirements.
      list.sort_by_key(
          |e| e.width
      );

      // move captured object out of environment.
      let record_text = String::from("sort.");
      let records: Vec<String> = Vec::new();

      //                                (FnMut)
      // BAD USAGE,failed to meet trait bound requirement.
      // because this closure will moves the local variable
      // @record_text out its body,move into @records.
      // after we moved the String object,@record_text will
      // be invalid.(move the value out of the closure by
      // transferring ownership)
      // this closure's trait is FnOnce.
      list.sort_by_key(
          |e| {
              records.push(record_text);
              e.width
          }
      );

      // FnMut
      let num_of_sort: u32 = 0;
      list.sort_by_key(
          |e| {
              num_of_sort += 1;
              e.width
          }
      );

Iterators
---------

many rust structures support iterator,for create an iterator over the object,
need to invoke member method,usually named iter().
the for-cycel to iterate each item in a sequence,is implicitly used iterator.

Iterator trait and the "next" method
------------------------------------

all iterators need to implement a trait named "Iterator",and that implementation
must contains a method named "next".
    pub trait Iterator {
        // define an associated type with this trait.
        type Item;

        fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item>;
    }
call next() on an iterator will change its internal state,thus the variable is
bound with an iterator must be mutable.
    let mut vec_iterator = local_vec.iter();
but there is an exception,when used an iterator in for-cycle,the cycle will
takes the iterator's ownership,thus the variable do not need to be mutable.
    let viter_for = local_vec.iter();
    for e in viter_for {
        ...
    }
iter() method need to return an iterator over immutable references.
into_iter() method need to return an iterator that takes the ownership of
elements in that container,and can be used to get the element itself.
iter_mut() method need to return an iterator over mutable references.

in the iterator trait,method invoke next() is called "consuming adapters",
because next() method will changes the iterator's internal state,step to next
element.(consuming adapter needs ownership of iterator)

method sum() defined in Iterator trait,will takes the ownership of that iterator,
and computes the sum from the sequence by invoke next() repeatedly.
    let result = viter_for.sum();

Other iterators
---------------

"Iterator adapters" are methods defined in Iterator trait,the method does not
consume iterator,instead,they makeup different iterators by changing some aspect
of the original iterator.

the map() method in Iterator trait,require a closure,and invoke it on each
element by iterate elements through the original iterator,then makeup a new
iterator which can be used to iterate the mapped elements.
    let mapped_iter = viter_for.map(|e| e * 2);

note that,iterator in rust is lazy,that means,the result would not be created
immediately,until we consume the iterator.
if we want to consume the new iterator and get all results,we can invoke the
collect() method in Iterator trait.
    let mapped_results: Vec<_> = viter_for.map(|e| e * 2).collect();

method filter() is defined in Iterator trait,it need a closure that returns
a boolean value.if true is returned,current element would be included into
this is making new iterator,otherwise,skip it.
    let filtered_results: = viter_for.filter(|e| e % 2 == 0);

! if an iterator is consumed,then the original becomes invalid.
  (ownership have transferred)
! many iterator adapter need a closure,we can let the closure captures the
  variables in local context.

Smart Pointers :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

in rust,reference only borrow data,but in many cases,smart pointer own the
data it pointed to,the smart pointer is provided by standard library.
rust smart pointer defined "Deref" and "Drop" traits,the "Deref" trait allow
the smart pointer to behave like a reference,and "Drop" trait allow user
defined destructor.

Box<T> smart pointer
--------------------

the Box<T> type smart pointer allow us to store data on heap rather than on
stack,but the metadata of the pointer still stored on the stack.

the cases Box<T> should be considered
    1> the size of an object can not be determined at compile time.
    2> there is a large amount of data,and we want to transfer ownership
       but ensure no copying.
    3> for user defined special type has particular trait.

we can create a new Box smart pointer through its new() member method.
    let sp = Box::new(@value);
above statement will declare an immutable variable bind to a Box,and where
@value is the value we want to stored on the heap.
when @sp goes out of its scope,drop() method of this smart pointer will be
called,the heap area would be clean.

! Trait object
    we can let generic type of smart pointer to be a trait,then we can use
    the smart pointer points to object of any type that implemented the
    specified trait.
      let copy_box: Box<dyn Copy> = Box::new(...);
      trait CustomTrait {

      }

      let custom_box: Box<dyn CustomTrait> = Box::new(...);
    a little similar to C++ base class pointer to derived class object.
    # keyword "dyn" is a prefix used to define a Trait object.

Enabling Recursive Types with Box
---------------------------------

"recursive type" can have another object of the same type as the part.
because recursive type could theoretically continue infinitely,so rust can not
know its total size.
    enum ConsList<T> {
        Cons(T, ConsList<T>),
        Nil,
    }

    let cons_list: ConsList<i32> =
        Cons(1, Cons(2, Nil));
the above code would not compiled,rust will requires we use Box in the definition
because "recursive without indirection",it can not knows the size of this type.
    enum ConsList<T> {
        Cons(T, Box<ConsList<T>>),
        Nil,  //^rust been known size of Box object.
    }

    let cons_list: ConsList<i32> =
        Cons(1, Box::new(Cons(2, Box::new(Nil))));

Treating Smart Pointers Like Regular References
-----------------------------------------------

in C++,we can overload the dereference operator '*',to customize the behavior
of this operator for user defined type.
    value_type operator*();
in rust,we can do the same thing through "Deref" trait.
    // tuple struct.
    struct CustomSP<T>(T);

    impl<T> CustomSP<T> {
        fn new(v: T) -> CustomSP<T> {
            CustomSP(v)
        }   
    }

    impl<T> Deref for CustomSP<T> {
        // trait associated type.
        // @Target is a member of Deref trait.
        type Target = T;

        // dereference method,the operator*().
        // let it returns a reference,because
        //     *(sp.deref())
        fn deref(&self) -> &Self::Target {
            &self.0
        }
    }

Deref coercion converts a reference to a type that implements the "Deref" trait
into a reference to another type.
    &String => &str | because String implemented Deref trait.
this is useful on arguments to a function or a member method,this Deref coercion
happens automatically when pass a _reference_ to a particular type's value as an
argument to a function or member method that does not match the parameter type.
similar to C++ implicitly type conversion,but in C++,there at most only one
user-defined convert function can be called,but rust no such limitation.
! need use "std::ops::Deref".
! rust does deref coercion if 
      1> &T => &U,T: Deref<Target = U>

         have a &T,and T implements Deref for type U,
         get &U instead &T.

      2> &mut T => &mut U,T: DerefMut<Target = U>

         mutable version.

      3> &mut T => &U,T: Deref<Target = U>

         rust coerce a mutable reference to an immutable one.
         the reverse is not possible.(borrow rule)

DerefMut trait
--------------

there is another "Defer" trait for mutable version.
    impl DerefMut for <type> {
        fn deref_mut(&mut self) -> &Self::<specified-type>;
    }
    
    // immutable variable can not be borrowed as mutable.
    let mut int_sp = CustomSP::new(10);
    *int_sp = 20;
note that,the "DerefMut" trait inherits "Target" from the "Deref" trait,thus
we do not need to use additional type-definition to define a trait associated
type.
! need use "std::ops::DerefMut".

Cleanup with Drop trait
-----------------------

the Drop trait can let us to define customized destructor for object.
for a smart pointer,destructor need to deallocate the heap space,thus
this trait is very important to heap based objects to avoid memory
leak.
Drop trait requires one member method named "drop",it takes a mutable "self"
reference.
    impl<T> Drop for <type> {
        fn drop(&mut self) { }
    }
! Drop trait is included in prelude,same as Option<> and Result<>.
! if we want to drop object early before it goes out scope,we need invoke
  the standard library function std::mem::drop() to do this,not the drop()
  in Drop trait.
  function std::mem:drop() also is included in prelude.    
  # std::mem::drop() takes ownership of the object.

Reference-Counted Smart Pointer
-------------------------------

the rust type Rc<T> allows share ownership between several entities.
Rc<T> is only for use in single-threaded scenario.
    let cons_list_1 = Rc::new(Cons(1, Rc::new(Cons(2, Rc::new(Nil)))));
    let cons_list_2 = Cons(0, Rc::clone(&cons_list_1));
    let cons_list_3 = Cons(-1, Rc::clone(&cons_list_2));
the member method Rc::clone() can copy an object is type of Rc<T>,shallow copying
only.
    cons_list_2:
        (0, => --+
                 |    
                 V
    cons_list_1: Rc<>(1, => Rc<>(2, => Rc<>(Nil
                 ^
    cons_list_3: |
        (-1, => -+
Rc<> is included in the namespace std::rc::Rc,we need to bring it into local
namespace.
member method strong_count(@rc) of Rc<> can retrieve the reference count of the
Rc<> smart pointer.
    Rc::strong_count(&rc);
! Rc<> is immutable,we can not use it to modify the value of oject it points to.
! Rc<> will be destroyed only when its strong count becomes _zero_,regardless to
  what weak count is.

RefCell<T>,Interior Mutability
------------------------------

interior mutability is a design pattern in rust to allows us to modify an object
through immutable reference.
normally,the borrow rule forbit this pattern,but we can enforce modification
through the "unsafe" pattern.
"unsafe" means user checks borrow rules manually,do not rely on compiler to check
them.

rust type RefCell<T> are used to enforce borrow rules' invariants at runtime.
RefCell<> can only be used in single-threaded scenario,and it can not share the
ownership between several entities.but different from Rc<T>,RefCell<T> supports
to immutable or mutable borrow checked at runtime,where Rc<T> is checked at 
compile time.because this ability,we can mutate the object inside the RefCell<>
even when the RefCell<> is immutable at runtime.

member method borrow_mut() of RefCell<> can be used to makeup a mutable reference
to that object the RefCell<> is pointing.
! return RefMut<_, T> type,has DerefMut trait.

member method borrow() of RefCell<> can be used to makeup an immutable reference
to that object the RefCell<> is pointing.
! return Ref<_, T> type,has Deref trait only.

we can let Rc<T> object to holds a RefCell<T> object,and in which the real object
is stored.then we can share ownership via the Rc<>,and we can use the immutable
Rc<> to modify the real object at runtime.
    let share_ownership: Rc<RefCell<i32>> = Rc::new(RefCell::new(20));
    let mut modifier1 = (*share_ownership).borrow_mut();
                      // *share_ownership.borrow_mut()
                      // access to the real object directly.
    *modifier1 = 30;
! the borrow rules will be checked at runtime on RefCell<>,thus if we borrow
  the object more than once,program will panic.

!! reference cycle can leak memory.
   in C++,when use std::shared_ptr<>,reference cycle may occurs,
   but std::weak_ptr<> can prevent this.
   in rust
       enum ConsList {
           Cons(i32, RefCell<Rc<ConsList>>),
           Nil,
       } // bring reference cycle problem.
   and there also has type Weak<T>,can be used to prevent this problem.
   the member method downgrade(&rc) of Rc<> can be used to makeup an object
   it type of weak<>,and the Rc<> object's weak count will be increased by 1.
   weak<> do not share ownership,if we want to use a weak<> object,we need to
   invoke member method upgrade(&self) on it,this method returns Option<Rc<T>>.
   if the original Rc<> been cleanup,then None will be contained in the Option.
       let cons_list = Cons(1, RefCell::new(Rc::new(Nil)));
       let weak_ref = Rc::downgrade(cdr(&cons_list).borrow());
       // suppose cdr() returns reference to next element in Cons.
       
       let rc_ref = weak_ref.upgrade(); // Option<>.

Concurrency in Rust :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

concurrent execution in rust depends on borrow checking and type system,to change
the runtime error of multi-threaded to the compile time error.

create a new thread
-------------------

"thread" module in standard library provides interfaces for multi-threaded
environment.
function std::thread::spawn(@closure) can be used to create a new thread from
current thread.
    std::thread::spawn(
        || { ... }
    );
when the main thread completed,all spawned threads are shutdown,except we detach
them from main thread.
function std::thread::sleep(@duration) can be used to let current thread sleep
a while.
    std::thread::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_millis(100));
                      //^ rust time duration,will sleep 100ms.
    
the return type of spawn() function is JoinHandle<T>,we can store them somewhere
when we spawn the new thread,and use the handle to wait for it finish in the
main thread.
    let handle = std::thread::spawn(|| { ... });
    ...
    handle.join().unwrap();
the member method join() of JoinHandle<T> will returns a Result object,then we
can know whether the new thread is joined successfully.

if our main thread is a producer,and new thread is consumer,when we spawn a 
new thread,we should use "move" keyword on the closure to transfer the ownership
of specified object to the new thread's context,because main thread may give up
to the maintenance of that object for some reason.
    let vec_for_thread: Vec<i32> = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let new_thread_handle = thread::spawn(
        move || {
            ... // used @vec_for_thread.
        }
    );
    ...
    new_thread_handle.join().unwrap();
through transfer ownership,the main thread is no longer need to invoke the
std::mem::drop() to destroy that resource used by new thread.   

Thread communicate via rust channel
-----------------------------------

rust provides channel type to let upstream send message to downstream,that is
included in the std::sync::mpsc module,function mpsc::channel() can be used to
create such channel.
! mpsc => Multiple Producer,Single Consumer

             // upstream
             B    C    D    ...
              \   |   /    
               \  |  /
                \ | /
                  +
                  |
                  |
                  V
                  A
             // downstream

mpsc::channel() returns a tuple,the first element is transmitter(tx),and the
second element is the receiver(rx).
    let (tx, rx) = mpsc::channel();
    let new_thread_handle = thread::spawn(
        move || {
            tx.send(@val).unwrap();
        }
    );
    ...
    let v = rx.recv().unwrap();
    ...
    new_thread_handle.join().unwrap();
member function send() of tx need a message that will be sent to downstream,
and return a Result object. // send() takes ownership.
member function recv() of rx can be used to receive the message from upstream,
and return a Result object. // recv() gets ownership.
! recv() may block current thread,another member function try_recv() would not
  block current thread,and it also return Result<T, E>.
  if upstream has shutdown the stream,then recv() of rx would return an error
  to signal that no more messages will be coming.

we can transfer ownership of an object via channel.
    let to_be_sent = ...;
    ...
    move || {
        tx.send(to_be_sent).unwrap();
    }
    ...
    let received_obj = rx.recv().unwrap();
    // assert(@received_obj == @to_be_sent).

if we send several messages from upstream through send() method,then each send
request will be queued in the order of send() is called,and recv() on rx will
get the messages in a right order by call recv() several times.

if we want to create several producer,then we need to clone tx for each upstream
thread.
    let (tx, rx) = mpsc::channel();
    let tx1 = tx.clone();
    let tx2 = tx.clone();
    ...
in this case,the upstream threads may executes concurrent,thus the messages from
produces may mixed.
    sender1: one, two, three
    sender2: four, five, six
    receiver: one, two, four, five, three, six
    // because system interrupt.
if we want the messages follow a certain order,we need to sync them manually.

Use Mutex to sync threads in rust
---------------------------------

Mutex,the mutual exclusion,at any time,only one entity is allowed accesses to
the special shared object.
rust provides mutex data structure,the Mutex<T>,is inclued in std::sync::Mutex.
constructor new(@shared_object) method of Mutex<> can be used to create and
initialize a mutex object.
    let lm: Mutex<i32> = Mutex::new(20);
new() needs to take ownership of @shared_object,if we pass a value to it rather
than a been created object,it need to create such object at internal space.
different from C and C++ mutex,it stores the shared object in its internal space,
but C and C++ mutex only is a lock.

member method lock() of Mutex<> returns LockResult type,which will wraps an
object is type of MutexGuard,we can call to unwrap() method on that result
to retrieve the wrapped object.
the MutexGuard type has implemented Deref DerefMut Drop trait,thus we can access
to the guarding data like a SmartPointer.
    println!("shared object is {}", *lm.lock().unwrap());
when the MutexGuard object goes out of its scope,automatically Drop will happens,
thus the mutex will become unlock state.(similar to C++ std::lock_guard<>)

there is another problem,if we want to access the mutex in the spawned thread,
the closure of the thread need to capture the mutex.
if we let the thread capture the mutex by reference,the mutex's livetime is
maintained by current thread,if current thread finished,the mutex object will
be destroyed,this is an error if the new thread access to the mutex.
so we need capture it by take ownership,but current thread is not able to
access to the mutex at this time.
we must ensure the current thread and the new thread share ownership of the
mutex object.

we can not use Rc<>,because it is only for single-thread.
rust provides another data structure named Arc<T> can be used to solve this
problem.(Arc<T> => Atomic Reference Count)
Arc<T> is inclued in module std::sync:atomic,it is the atomic version of
Rc<T>.
    let arc: Arc<Mutex<i32>> = Arc::new(Mutex::new(20));
    let arc_for_thread = Arc::clone(&arc);
    let t1 = thread::spawn(
        move || {
            ... // capture @arc_for_thread by take ownership.
        }
    );
the member method Arc::clone(&@Arc_object) can help us to make a clone of the
original Arc<> object,we can move the clone into new thread.the mutex wrapped
in the Arc<> object as long as valid until the strong count become _zero_.

Send and Sync traits
--------------------

the key concurrency concepts are embedded in the rust language,not in the
standard library,they are std::marker traits,Send and Sync.

Send marker trait,the ownership of objects of the type implemented Send trait
can be transferred between threads.
almost every rust type implemented Send trait.
! Rc<> is used for single-thread only,because no Send trait is implemented for
  it.
  if we clone a new Rc<>,the strong count of them would be updated at the same
  time.
      Rc1 [ ... | strong count ]
                  ^  
                  |
                  +-----+
                        |
                        V
      Rc2 clone [ ... | strong count ]

  Arc<> implemented Send trait,thus it can be used for multi-threads.

Sync marker trait,refer to the type implementing Sync trait between multiple
threads is safe.
T implements Sync if &T implements Send,reference can be sent safely to another
thread.
primitive types all implement Sync.
! Rc<> does not implement Sync trait.
  Mutex<> does implement Sync trait.
  RefCell<> is borrow checked at runtime,thus it is not thread-safe.

implement Send and Sync manually is unsafe.
the types composed entirely of other types that implement the Send and Sync
traits also automatically implement Send and Sync.
marker traits,do not even have any methods to implement,just for
enforce invariants related to concurrency.

Rust Asynchronous Programming :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Futures and the Async syntax
----------------------------

a future is a value that may not be ready now,but will become ready at some
point in the future.(such C++ promise)
rust has the "Future" trait,futures are types that implement the "Future" trait.

the keyword "async" to blocks and functions to specify that they can be interrupted
and resumed.
in the "async" block,or in the "async" function,keyword "await" can be used to
await a future.(potential spot for pause and resume)
the checking to a future is called "polling".

for code used async and await keywords,compiler will compiles them to equivalent
code using the Future trait,same as for loop to Iterator trait.
the keyword "await" can only be used in "async" block or function,in other word,
it can only be executed in asynchronous context.(main() is synchronous context)

when runtime executing the async code,it will be blocked at the position where
"await" is appears in the original code,because it is required to await a future.
    let fut1 = async {
        ...
    };

    let fut2 = async {
        ...
    };

    futures::block_on(
        async move {
            ...
            fut1.await; // runtime awaiting the future @fut1.
            ...
            fut2.await; // runtime awaiting the future @fut2.
        }
    );
if we start an asynchronous context,the synchrnous contex in which this asynchrnous
context is started will be blocked until the asynchrnous context finished.
(we usualy call the synchronous context the "top-level")
    fn main() {

        // top-level

        futures::block_on(
            // asynchrnous context.

            async {
                ...
            }
        );

        // main() will be blocked until futures::block_on() returns,
        // because main() is synchrnous context.
    }   

! in rust,"future" is laziness,we can seen the result when we ask the it with the
  "await" keyword,the future related code will runs when it is necessary.
! "await" is a postfix keyword,usually appears after the expression we want to
  await.
      let x = return_future().await;

async function
    async fn <function-name>(<parameter-list>) -> <return_type> {
        <body>
    }

    // mark a function as an async function,
    // then we can use "await" keyword on the
    // function's result.
    // rust compiler will help us to wrap the
    // result into Future type.
    async fn func() -> <return_type> {
        ... // body.
    }

async block
    async <optional move keyword> {
        ...
    }
    ! keyword "move" has the same effect as in a closure definition,
      means take ownership of the object captured in the block.
    ! async block will produces an anonymous future.we can give the
      anonymous future a variable binding to refer it.
          let the_future = async {
              ...
          };


    // non-async function from async function.

                           // +--> trait associated type
                           // |        +--> type we want return
                           // |        |
    fn func() -> impl Future<Output = <type-name>> {

        // we return an async block from this function,it will be
        // wrapped into a an object whose type has Future trait.
        async move {
            ...
        } // block is a compound expression.
          // this async block should produces
          // a result is type of the real type we
          // want return.

    }   

in rust,we can not await a future in main() function,because async code needs a
"runtime",it is a rust crate manages the details of executing asynchronous code.
main() funcion can initialize a runtime,but it is not a runtime itself.
any rust program used async,need a runtime where to execute the futures.

the await point--where used await keyword,represents a place where control is
handed back to the runtime.(runtime use the state machine to handles async
expressions have received,rustc can creates and manages the state machine data
structures for async code automatically)

! some runtime may provides select() function,it should able to polling futures
  to return the first one became ready state,we can "await" on the future to
  get the result.
! the order "await" appears in code,is the order those code is executed by the
  asynchronous runtime.if we put "await" keywords in one async block,then they
  are executed linearly.
      async {
          ...           // first to be executed
          xxx.await;    // pause
          ...           // second to be executed
          yyy.await;    // pause 
      }
  similar to the memory barrier.
  it we separate the await code into several individual async block,and pass 
  those futures to runtime,they might be executed interactively,may be not,depends
  on runtime.(for polling mode,this should be interactively)
      A => B => A => B => ...

the rust only pauses async blocks and hands control back to a runtime at an
await point,the inverse is also true.(the future being awaited is not ready)
if we put a long-running work or expensive setup into one async block without
await point,then other futures would not get progress because runtime has not
get control back.
    let async1 = async {
        ... // long-running
        future.await;
    };

    let async2 = async {
        ... // long-running
        future.await;
    };

    // async2 gets running after async1
    // did "future.await;".
    // suppose select() handles futures in polling mode.
    future::select(async1, async2).await;
@async1 get running at first,when it reached await point,hands control back to
the runtime,then runtime let @async2 get running.when @async2 reached await point,
hands control back to runtime.runtime next let @async1 get running,but there is
no rest statement can executes,so the first future finished.runtime let @async2
get continue,but same as @async1,no more statement can executes,the second future
finished.now,runtime get into idel state.
through future,the workflow of different parts of a program become visible,we
can know where the code paused,and when it get resumed.

Stream,Future,and Iterator
--------------------------

a stream can be used to store the data will coming sequentially.
for each timepoint,the data has come into the stream,we can think a promise in
future has satisfied.
                                         will come
                                         |<----->|
    |====================================-------->
     |<----------- existing ----------->|

because we do not know when is the future the data we expected get come into
stream,thus,stream is asynchronous.
if we want to access the data in a sequence,we usually make use of an iterator.
but iterator is synchronous,so we need a way to combine asynchronous stream and
synchronous iterator.

we can let a stream provides an iterator,or we can use an iterator of a sequence
to makeup a stream.
    let seq: Vec<i32> = vec![0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
    let it = seq.iter(); 

    // makeup stream from an iterator.
    let stream = stream_from_iterator(it);
    while let Some(d) = stream.next().await {
        ...
    }

    let file = open_file(@filepath);
    let fstream = file.stream();
    let fstream_it = fstream.iter();
    while let Some(d) = fstream_it.next().await {

    }
for asynchronous stream,such network packages,file stream,we can let runtime
suspends the handler until the data comes,and other part of code,we can
continue to deal with another work.when we realy need the future's result,
we can await to wait for stream returns result.
so,at other view point,stream is seem like an asynchronous iterator.
    pub trait Stream {
        type Item;

        fn poll_next(self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context<'_>)
        -> Poll<Option<Self::Item>>;
    }

    trait StreamExt: Stream {
        async fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item>
        where
            Self: Unpin;
    }   

! usually Stream trait is the low-level stream,and StreamExt trait is the
  high-level APIs over low-level stream.
  

A Closer Look at the Traits for Async
-------------------------------------

the Future trait usually has a method named "poll",and which will return a
wrapper,which will wraps the result of poll.
! Ready(T) => future ready
  Pending  => is pending
we usually do not need to invoke poll() method directly,compiler will does this
for us if we used "await".the future,generally can only be polled by once,if we
poll the future again,may cause panic.(maybe some futures supports more than once
polls)
    match return_a_future().poll() {
        Ready(v) => match v {
                        Some(d) => ... ,
                        None => ... ,
                    },
        Pending => ... , // need to hand control to runtime,let it
                         // checks other futures.
    }

the Pin Type and the Unpin Trait,usually comes with poll() method together.
    pub trait Future {
        type Output;
        
        fn poll(self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context<'->) -> Poll<Self::Output>;
    }
the "self" annotation has some different trait from annotation for other function
parameters.
    > it tells rust what type "self" must be for the method to be called.
    > it can not be just any type,it is restricted to the type on which the
      method is implemented,a reference or smart pointer to that type,or
      a Pin wrapping a reference to that type.

Pin Type,is a wrapper for pointer-like types,but it is not a pointer itself,
and does not have any behavior of its own,it is purely a tool the compiler can
use to enforce constraints on pointer usage.
it pins the exact object,not the pointer,if we pinned an object,then it can not
be moved in memory(the memory location can not changes).
Box object can be moved around,but the object is pointed previously need to stay
in the same place,Pin Type provides this guarantee.

Unpin Trait is a marker trait,no functionality of its own.it only to tell compiler
it is safe to use the type implementing a given trait in a particular context.
for any type it is safe(no internal reference),compiler implements UnPin trait
for this type automaticall.such type does not need to uphold the guarantees to be
safe whenever a pointer to that type is used in a Pin Type.
! Unpin is normal case,!Unpin is special case.
  whether a type implements Unpin or !Unpin,only matters when we using a pinned
  mutable pointer to that type. 
! Unpin => self-referential

a Future will be compiled to a state-machine by compiler at compile time,for
safety,rustc must checks objects ownership and lifetime in the flow.if we want
to move the Future type object produced by async block into collection,we need
to Pin it because it has not implement Unpin(it has internal references).
macro pin!(@obj) can be used to pin @obj,to keep its memory location unchanged.
    let fut1 = pin!(async { ... });
    let fut2 = pin!(async { ... });

    let fvec: Vec<Pin<&mut dyn Future<Output = ()>>> = vec![fut1, fut2];

! Pin Type is defined in module std::pin,we can bring them into current scope
  through
    use std::pin::{Pin, pin};    


[sync operation and async operation both running on runtime]
                                                 
++>  ++++> async operation +++++++> await +++++++++++++++++ async end 
+                              |||                       +          -
+                               |                        +          -
+                              |||                       +          -
+    ----> sync operation ---> start async operation ----> ... ----->
+                                                    ^   +          -
+                                                    -   V          V
+++ [====================================================+==========-]
                            rust runtime

Rust Object-Oriented Programming
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Object-Oriented programs are made up of objects.an object packages both data and
the procedures that operate on the data,the procedures are typically called
methods or operations.
in rust for do this,we can use structure and implementation features.

encapsulation,means that the implementation details of an object are not 
accessible to code using that object,hides the details.the rust keyword "pub"
can change the accessibility of an object,default it should be private.
    pub struct Average {
        sum: i32,
        avg: i32,
        count: i32,
    }

    impl Average {
        fn add_number(&mut self, v: i32) {
            self.sum += v;
            self.count += 1;
            self.avg = self.sum / self.count;
        }

        pub fn add(&mut self, v: i32) {
            add_number(self, v);
        }
        
        pub fn sub(&mut self, v: i32) {
            add_number(self, v * -1);
        }

        pub fn avg(&self) -> i32 {
            if self.count == 0 {
                0
            } else {
                self.avg
            }
        }

        pub fn reset(&mut self) {
            self.sum = 0;
            self.avg = 0;
            self.count = 0;
        }
    }

Inheritance as a Type System and as Code Sharing
------------------------------------------------

rust has no inheritance,if we want a struct inherits the parent struct's fields
and methods,must use a macro.

the reasons need to use inheritance
    1> for code reuse.
       for do this in rust,we can define the default implementation for a
       trait,and define special implementation for a certain type.
    2> for enable a child type to be used in the same places as the parent type,
       the "polymorphism".
       rust use generic type and trait bounds to enable "polymorphism",it is
       "parametric polymorphism".

Using Trait Objects to Abstract over Shared Behavior
----------------------------------------------------

if we want some types has a common behavior,then we should define a trait for
them,and give the default implementation for that common behavior.
    trait CustomCommon {
        type RetType;
        fn common(&mut self) -> Self::RetType;
    }

    impl CustomCommon for CustomStruct {
        type RetType = CustomStructRetType;
        fn common(&mut self) -> Self::RetType {
            ...
        }
    }
the keyword "dyn" used in a Box can let us to declare trait object,it can points
to any type that implemented the specified trait.
    // for the trait associated type,we need to specify it in
    // the Box's generic type description.
    let mut CustomStruct_collection: Vec<Box<dyn CustomCommon<RetType = @type>>>
        = vec![Box::new(CustomStruct::new())];
    CustomStruct_collection[0].common();
if we specified the trait associated type in the detail,then we must ensure the
Box's generic type description match it,the Box can only points to the
object whose trait associated type is same as the type appears in generic type
description.
    Box<@Trait<@TraitAssociatedType = @type>> ...

if an object should be composed by some other objects they have implemented the
common trait,then we can collect them into a container.
    pub trait CommonTrait {
        fn method(&mut self);
    }

    struct CS { }
    impl CS { ... }
    impl CommonTrait for CS { ... }

    struct CS1 { }
    impl CS1 { ... }
    impl CommonTrait for CS { ... }

    struct CS2 { }
    impl CS2 { ... }
    impl CommonTrait for CS { ... }

    struct CallMethod {
        obj: Vec<Box<dyn CommonTrait>>,
    }

    impl CallMethod {
        fn call(&mut self) {
            for object in self.obj.iter() {
                object.method();
            }
        }
    }

    let mut collection = CallMethod {
        obj: vec![Box::new(CS::new()),
                  Box::new(CS1::new()),
                  Box::new(CS2::new())
                 ],
    };

    collection.call();

Dynamic Dispatch
----------------

when the compiler can not tell at compile time which method we are calling,
compiler will emits code that at runtime will know which method to call.
when we using trait object,dynamic dispatch will be used,rust uses the pointers
inside the trait object to know which method to call.
in C++,such pointers are collected into a virtual function table.
! incur runtime cost.

Implementing an Object-Oriented Design Pattern
----------------------------------------------

in Object-Oriented design,we usually need a state pattern.
the state represents current state of the object,and constraints its behaviors.
the traditional state pattern is use a data member in that object to represents
its state,the member methods of that object need to check its current state to
determine whether current action is allowed.

traditional state pattern
    struct OBJ {
        state: i32
        ...
    }

    impl OBJ {
        fn do_something(&self) {
            match state {
                @state1 => @action1,
                ...
            }
        }

        fn do_something1(&self) {
            match state {
                @state1 => @action1,
                ...
            }
        }
    }
the traditional state pattern will bring repeated code into each member methods
for check current state.

encapsolute state object
    struct OBJ {
        state: Box<dyn StateTrait>,
        ...
    }

    trait StateTrait {
        fn do_something(obj: &OBJ);
        ...
    }

    struct State1 { }
    impl StateTrait for State1 { ... }

    impl OBJ {
        fn do_something(&self) {
            if self.state == @State1 {
                self.state.do_something(self);
                ...
            }
            ...
        }
    }
through encapsolute state object,we can make some wrappers in the object that
uses the state object.and in the definition of state object,we put the real logic
into its methods,and let those wrappers invoke the methods in state object,to
handles real works.

encode state object to type
    struct OBJ {
        ...
    }

    impl OBJ {
        fn full_features(&self) { ... }
        fn new() -> InitialOBJ { ... }
    }

    struct InitialOBJ {
        ...
    }

    impl InitialOBJ {
        fn become_progressing(self) -> ProgressingOBJ { ... }
    }

    struct ProgressingOBJ {
        ...
    }

    impl ProgressingOBJ {
        fn become_OBJ(self) -> OBJ { ... }
    }
through encode state object to different types,we can restrict what the actions
can be taken on the object in a certain state.any calling to disallowed actions
will get compiler error.

for the type of state object,if we do not encode state to type,we should use
Option<> instead use Enum.because,if we use Enum,then we need to put all possible
patterns into match-expressions,this is a dirty work,and easy to make mistake.
by use Option<Box<dyn @Trait>>,we just need to handle the Some(v) case,because
we can design the state object to let it never becomes None.when the state object
migrate state from old state to new state,we should let the code takes the
ownership of the old state,to consume it for create a new state.
    fn do_something(&mut self) {
        if let Some(s) = self.state.take() {
            self.state = s.do_something(self);
            ...
        }
        ...
    }

    impl StateTrait for State {
        fn do_something(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn StateTrait> { ... }
    }

    /**
     * the take() member method of Option<> can take ownership of the value
     * in Some() rather than borrow it,we can move it and consume it.
     * at there,it is a trait object Box<dyn StateTrait>.
     * we can only invoke take() if and only if the Option<> object is mutable.
     * after we take the ownership(),the Option<> object becomes None.
     */

    fn do_something1(&self) -> &InternalDataType {
        self.state.as_ref().unwrap().do_something1(self)
    }

    impl StateTrait for State {
        fn do_something1(&self, obj: OBJ) { ... }
    }
    /**
     * if do_something1() do not change the state,we should borrow the value
     * in Option<> rather than take ownership,thus we invoke as_ref() on it.
     */

Patterns and Matching :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

All the Places Patterns Can Be Used
-----------------------------------

the first place is the match-expression,we have known that.

we can also use pattern in the "let" statement,use this style can allow us to
get the data members in a tuple(destructure a tuple).
    let <pattern> = <expression>;
    let (x, y, z) = (1, 2, 3);
if the number of variabels in pattern is not matches to the expression,compiler
will throw error.

the "if let" flow control statement can use pattern.
    if let Some(v) = x {
        ...
    }

"while let" loop can use pattern.
    while let Ok(v) = rx.recv() {
        ...
    }

"for" loop can use pattern.
    for (key, value) in &hashmap {
        ...
    }

in function parameter list,pattern can be used.
    fn func(&(x, y): &(i32, i32)) { ... }
    let x = (10, 20);
    func(&x);

Refutability: Whether a Pattern Might Fail to Match
---------------------------------------------------

pattern has two forms,refutable and irrefutable.
patterns will match for any possible value passed are irrefutable.
patterns can fail to match for some possible value are refutable.
    let x = 20; // irrefutable,@x only match 20
    if let Ok(e) = r { ... } // refutable,@r might be Err

    let Some(x) = option; // compile error,refutable pattern.

"let","for",function parameters,can only accept irrefutable patterns.
"if let","while let","let...else" can accept refutable and irrefutable patterns.

Pattern Syntax
--------------

matching literals.
    let obj = 10;
    match obj {
        1 => <action>,
        2 => <action>,
        ...
        _ => <action>,
    }

the named variable in @pattern is irrefutable.
    let obj = get_result();
    match obj {
        // start a new scope.

        Some(v) => <action>,
        Some(20) => <action>,
        None => <action>,
    }

matching multiple patterns.
    match @obj {
        <patternA> | <patternB> => <action>,
        ...
    }

matching ranges of values with "..=".
    match @obj {
        1..=6 => <action>
        ...
    }
    // if @obj is in [1, 6],the first arm will be executed.

    // not only integers,the characters in the range is OK.
    match @char {
        'a'..='f' => <action>,
        ...
    }
! when we match the value in a range,we need patterns to cover the ranges
  we do not interested in.
      match u32_v {
          0..=8 => <action>,
          9..=u32::MAX => <action>,
      }
      // or
      match u32_v {
          0..=8 => <action>,
          _ => <action>,
      }

pattern can be used to destructure structs,enums,and tuples to use different
parts of them.

for struct.
    struct S {
        x: i32,
        y: f32,
    }

    let s = S { x: 2, y: 2.0 };
    let S { x: @obj1, y: @obj2 } = s;
    // @obj1 bind to @x of s,@obj2 bind to @y of s.
when we destructure the struct object,for the data member whose type has not
Copy trait is implemented,move semantics will be applied,thus ownership will
be taken by the variable.
    struct S {
        x: String,
    }
    ...
    let S { x: str } = S_obj;
    let srx = &mut S_obj.x; // error
because we can destructure struct,thus we can use this form in match-expression.
    let S_obj = S { x: 2, y: 8 };  // -----+
    match S_obj {                  //      |
        S { x: 2, y } => ... ,     // <----+ match this arm,@y bind to 8
        S { x, y } => ... ,        
        S { x,y: 0 } => ... ,      
        ...
    }

for enum.
    match E {
        <enum::enumerator> => <action>,
        ...
    }

    match E_Nested {
        <enum::enumerator(enum1::enumerator(v1, v2, ...))> => <action>,
        ...
    }

for tuples with structs.
    let ((tuplev1, tuplev2) , S { x: a, y: b }) =
        ((2, 4), S { x: 2, y: 4 });
    // @tuplev1 bind to 2.
    // @tuplev2 bind to 4.
    // @a bind to S::x == 2.
    // @b bind to S::y == 4.

we can use '_' pattern to ignore value in pattern.
    fn func(_: i32, necessary: &str) { ... }
    func(0, "call func");

    match result_obj {
        Some(_) => <action>,
        Err(_) => <action>,
    }

if we constructed a nested object,we can use '_' to ignore values in the inners.
    let some1 = Some(2);
    let some2 = Some(3);
    match (some1, some2) {
        (Some(_), Some(_)) => <action>,
        ...
    }

    let some3 = Some(4);
    match (some1, some2, some3) {
        (_, Some(_), Some(v)) => <action>, // ignore @some1,value in @some2.
        ...
    }

we can prefix a variable with '_',to represents this variable is unused,compiler
will not print unused variable warning,but the move/copy semantics still has
effect.(may take ownership,because binding still happens,even we do not use it)
but only '_' as variable,no move/copy will happens.
    let s = Some(String::from("some"));
    if let Some(_) = s {
        // the string object will not be moved,ownership
        // is not changed.
        ...
    }

    if let Some(_move_it) = s {
        // the string object is moved to @_move_it.
        ...
    }

the string ".." can be used to represents the remaining of the structure.
    let s = S { x: 2, y: 4, z: 8 };
    let S { x: a, .. } = s; // only bind @a to @x,ignore the remaining.

    match s {
        S { _, y, .. } => <action>, // only bind @y to @s.y 
        ...
    }

    let array_obj: [i32; 4] = [0, 1, 2, 3];
    match array_obj {
        [0, .., v] => <action>, // only bind @v to array_obj[@last_one],ignore
        ...                     // the elements between [0]--[@last_one].
    }
! ".." must be unambiguous.
      (.., v, ..) => ambiguous,cause compiler error.

condition checking can be used with match-expression's patterns.
    match x {
        Some(v) if v % 2 == 0 => <action>, // @v is even
        Some(v) => <action>,               // @v is odd
        ...
    }

    match v {
        0 | 1 | 2 if @cond => <action>, // (0 | 1 | 2) if <condition>
        ...                             // not 0 | 1 | (2 if <condition>)
    }

! match-expression only.

the at operator '@' can create a variable that holds a value at the same time
we testing the value for a pattern match.
    match some_obj {
        // test if the value in range [0, 4].
        Some(0..=4) => match some_obj {
                           // bind the value.
                           Some(v) => <action>,
                           ...
                       },
        ...
    }

    ||
    VV

    match some_obj {
        // test and bind the value if it in range [0, 4].
        Some(value @ 0..=4) => <action>,
        ...
    }

Advanced Features :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Unsafe Rust
-----------

unsafe rust does not enforce memory safety,provides extra features.
keyword "unsafe" can be used to start a block to contains unsafe code.
    unsafe {
        ...
    }
the features provided by unsafe are
    > derefer a raw pointer.
    > call an unsafe function or method.
    > access or modify a mutable static variable.
    > implement an unsafe trait.
    > access fields of union object.
! unsafe does not disable borrow checker and other safety checks.
  when we use the five features above,compiler will not checks them for
  memory safety.

raw pointer type in unsafe code
-------------------------------

the type *const T and *mut T are the immutable and mutable raw pointers,
respectively.immutable means the raw pointer can only be used for read data.

raw pointers trait
    > allowed to ignore the borrowing rules by having both immutable and mutable
      pointers or multiple mutable pointers to the same location.
    > no guarantee to point to valid memory.
    > allowed to be null.
    > do not implement any automatic cleanup.

declare raw pointers
    let mut num = 5;
    let irp = &raw const num; // create *const T
    let mrp = &raw mut num;   // create *mut T

    let addr = 0x07777ffeb;
    let mrp = addr as *mut i32; // create *mut T,value is 0x07777ffeb.
    // let irp = 0x07777ffeb as *const i32; => create *const T.

operator '*' can be used to derefer a raw pointer(only in unsafe block).
    unsafe {
        let x = *irp;   // value's type is T.
    }

unsafe keyword also can be used to indicates a unsafe function(similar to async).
    unsafe fn unsafe_function() { }

    unsafe {
        unsafe_function();
    }
! a function contains unsafe code does not mean we need to mark the entire 
  function as unsafe.generally,we can wrap unsafe code into a safe function,
  to build safe abstrction over unsafe code.
      use std::slice;

      fn return_raw_pointers(array: &mut [i32], mid: u32)
      -> (&mut [i32], &mut [i32]) {
          let size: usize = array.len();
          assert!(mid <= size);
          let rp = array.as_mut_ptr();

          // result of a unsafe block is the last expression.
          // both slice::from_raw_parts_mut() and add() of raw pointer are
          // unsafe function.
          unsafe {
              (
                  // slice::from_raw_parts_mut(@rp, @length) can be used to
                  // create a slice over a raw pointer.
                  slice::from_raw_parts_mut(rp, mid),

                  // member method add() of raw pointer can execute
                  // pointer addition.
                  slice::from_raw_parts_mut(rp.add(mid), size - mid),
              )
          }

      }

Using "extern" Functions to Call External Code
----------------------------------------------

keyword "extern" can let us to use a Foregion Function Interface(FFI),it is a
way for a programming language to define functions and enable a different
programming language to call those functions.
    unsafe extern "C" {
        fn abs(i: i32) -> i32;
    }

    unsafe {
        println!("abs is {}", abs(-2));
    }

we introduce an external function from C named abs(),and invoke it within the
unsafe code.we need to reforge its prototype into the rust format,as the
declaration.

the rust also supports call the rust function from other programming language.
#[unsafe(no_mangle)]
    this attribute is necessary for tell the rust compiler not to mangle the name
    of this function.
    # mangling is when a compiler changes the name we have given a function to
      a different name that contains more information for other parts of the
      compilation process to consume but is less human readable.

by combine the keywords "pub" and "extern",we can declare the function can be
called from other language.
    #[unsafe(no_mangle)]
    pub extern "C" fn call_rust_fn_from_c() { ... }

    // "C" has limited the programming language which can invoke this function.
    // now we can invoke call_rust_fn_from_c() from C code.

Accessing or Modifying a Mutable Static Variable
------------------------------------------------

unsafe allows us to operate mutable static variable.
    static mut STATIC_VAR: i32 = 2; // initialized to 2.

    unsafe {
        STATIC_VAR += 2; // now @STATIC_VAR is 4.
        let rp = &raw const STATIC_VAR;
        println!("value is {}", *rp);
    }

#[allow(static_mut_refs)]
    this attribute can tell compiler the function is allowed to use a reference
    to a mutable static variable.

Unsafe Trait
------------
    unsafe trait UnsafeTrait {
        ...
    }

    unsafe impl UnSafeTrait for <type> {
        ...
    }

a trait is unsafe when at least one of its methods has some invariant that the
compiler can not verify.
for the method in unsafe trait is not unsafe method,nor contains unsafe code,
we can invoke it in safe code.

Accessing Union Fields
----------------------

a union is similar to a struct,but only one declared field is used in a particular
instance at one time.
    union TheUnion {
        x: i32,
        y: i32,
        z: f32,
    }

    // the rest fields are arbitraty value,access them is OK,but
    // the values of them are meaningless.
    let u = TheUnion { x: 20 };
    
    unsafe {
        println!("u.x is {}", u.x);
    }

Advanced Traits
---------------

the trait associated type plays the role as a type placeholder,when a trait is
implemented for a certain type,this associated type will gets real type.
    trait UseAType {
        type inner_type;
        fn do_something(&self) -> Self::inner_type {
            Self::inner_type::new()
        }
    }
the disadvantage of generic type against trai associated type is,we need to
annotate the types in each implementation.
    trait TraitGT<T> {
        fn do_something(&self) -> T;
    }

    impl TraitGT<String> for TheStruct { }
    impl TraitGT<u32> for TheStruct { }
    impl TraitGT<TheStruct> for TheStruct { }

    let ts = TheStruct { };

    <TheStruct as TraitGT<String>>::do_something(&ts);
    <TheStruct as TraitGT<u32>>::do_something(&ts);
    <TheStruct as TraitGT<TheStruct>>::do_something(&ts);
trait is implemented for the certain structure multiple times,thus we need to
specify where the method we want to invoke come from,via the type annotation.
if we use the trait associated type,the trait for a certain type can only be
implemented once.

Default Generic Parameters and Operator Overloading
---------------------------------------------------

syntax to specify default generic parameter.
    struct TheStruct<T = u32> {
        x: T,
    }

    impl<T> TheStruct<T> {
        fn x(&self) -> &T { &self.x }
    }
we can not specify default generic type for the generic function.

default generic type is useful is with "operator overloading".note,we can not
makeup a new operator,or overload arbitrary operators.the allowed operations and
corresponding traits are listed in "std::ops",by implementing the traits
associated with the operator.
    struct TheStruct { }

    impl Add for TheStruct {
        fn add(self, rhs: TheStruct) -> TheStruct { ... }
    }
with default generic type.
    trait Add<Rhs = Self> {
        type Output;
        fn add(self, rhs: Rhs) -> Self::Output;
    }
in the previous example,we did not specify the certain type for @Rhs,thus it
will implicitly be the type we implement Add trait on it,it is TheStruct.

we can also specify the generic type,to achieve addition between two different
types if we have known the details of them.
    struct TheStruct { x: usize, }

    impl Add<String> for TheStruct {
        type Output = usize;
        fn add(self, rhs: String) -> Self::Output {
            self.x + rhs.len()
        }
    }

    let ts = TheStruct { ... };
    let str = String::from(...);
    let result = ts + str;  // operator overload.

the main usage of default generic type
    1> extend a type without breaking existing code.
    2> allow customization in specific cases most user wont need.

Disambiguating Between Identically Named Methods
------------------------------------------------

rust allows a type implements several traits,if the traits have the functions
as the same name,when we invoke the function,need to tell rust which one we
want to call.
    let ts = TheStruct { };
    Trait1::do_something(&ts);
    Trait2::do_something(&ts);
    Trait3::do_something(&ts);
    ...
    
    // no @self parameter functions.
    // if the methods have no @self parameter,then
    // there could be other types that implement
    // this trait,we need to specify which one
    // we want to invoke.
    <@certain_type as @trait>::method();
    ...

Supertraits
-----------

the first trait is relied by second trait is called a supertrait,so the second
trait can only be used for the type has implemented the first trait.
    struct TheStruct { }

    trait <first_trait> {
        ...
    }

    impl <first_trait> for TheStruct {
        ...
    }

    trait <second_trait>: <first_trait> {
        ...
    }

    impl <second_trait> for TheStruct {
        ...
    }
through this way,we can define what the type can use the specified feature.
! similar to adding a trait bound to another trait.

Implementing External Traits with the Newtype Pattern
-----------------------------------------------------

we can only implement a trait on a type when the trait is visible to the type,or
the type is visible to the trait.
but we can do this indirectly through a wrapper,and let the wrapper become a
brige between the external trait and the external type.
    // tuple struct.
    struct VecWrapper(Vec<i32>);

    impl fmt::Display for VecWrapper {
        fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter) -> fmt::Result {
            // we can construct a format string to contains
            // elements in the vector of this tuple struct(wrapper),
            // to print a vector through its wrapper.
            // # @self.0 is the vector in wrapper.
            ...
            write!(f, ...);
            ...
        }
    }

    let vec_wrapper: VecWrapper = VecWrapper(vec![...]);
    println!("vec_wrapper is {vec_wrapper}");

Advanced Types
--------------

we can use newtype pattern to enforce type safety and abstraction.
    struct NewU32(u32);

    fn func(v: NewU32) {
        ...
    }

    let new_v = NewU32(20);
    func(new_v);    // OK

    let u32_v = 20;
    func(u32_v);    // ERROR
even the inner of NewU32 is u32 type same as type of @u32_v,the function still
refuses pass an argument is type of u32 instead NewU32.
use this encapsolution,we can wrap the existed type to newtype to do type
abstraction,if later the inner of newtype is changed,its user do not need to
worry about that,because we have hidden the implementation detail.

the "type" keyword in rust can be used to make a type alias.
    type NewU32 = u32; // NewU32 is synonym of u32,now.
we have known this keyword in trait associated type,there is its another
feature.
the type alias is different from newtype pattern,where the place need the original
type can use the alias as instead.
    fn func(x: u32);
    let new_v: NewU32 = 20;
    func(new_v); // OK
type alias can help us to reduce repetition,
    Box<dyn Fn() + Send + 'static> // Box type

    let lf: Box<dyn Fn() + Send + 'static> = Box::new(|| println!("func"));

    type StaticSendFunc = Box<dyn Fn() + Send + 'static>;
    let lf1: StaticSendFunc = Box::new(|| println!("lf1"));
like the "typedef" in C and C++.
we can use generic type in type alias,let the type can adaptive different cases.
    // we can ignore std::io::Error now.
    type Result<T> = Result<T, std::io::Error>;

rust has a special type named '!' that is known in type theory lingo as the
"empty type",it has no values.
or called it "never type",because it stands in the place of the return type when
a function will never return.
function that return never type is called "diverging function".
    fn do_exit(task: Task) -> ! {
        ...
        schedule();
    }
we can not create an object is type of '!',thus such function can not create
return value,it can never possibly return.
! '!' can be used in match-expression arms.because match-expression requires
  each arm has the same type,if one arm return '!' type,then this type will be
  ignored by compiler.
  panic!() has the never type,so we can use it in match-expression arms and
  compiler does not complain.
  a loop expression do not has condition to break cycle,type of its value is
  the '!' type.

the concept of "dynamically sized types",sometimes referred to as DSTs or 
unsized types,these types allow us to use the type its size can only be known
at runtime.
for example,the type "str" is DST,and we can not create value is type of DST
directly,instead,we need to use the slice type "&str".
slice data structure only stores the starting position and the length of the slice.
hence,we can know the size of slice type at compile time,size of memory address
data and the size of length data.
dynamically sized types in rust have an extra bit of metadata that stores the
size of the dynamic information,we must always put values of dynamically sized
types _behind_ a pointer of some kind.
    Box<str>
    &str
every trait is a dynamically sized type,we can create trait object.
    Box<dyn <trait-name>>
    &dyn <trait-name>
rust provides "Sized" trait to determine whether or not a type's size is known
at compile time,this trait is automatically implemented for everything its size
can be known at compile time,in addition,rust implicitly adds a bound on "Sized"
to every generic function.
    fn generic_func<T>(v: T);
    fn generic_func<T: Sized>(v: T);
generally,generic function can only works on types that size is known at compile
time,but we can relax this restriction.
    // we use &T to instead T in parameter list,this is because
    // the type T may not be Sized,in this case,we must use
    // a pointer to wrap it.
    fn generic_func<T: ?Sized>(v: &T);
a trait bound on "?Sized" means "T may or may not be Sized".
"?<trait-name>" can only be available on "Sized" trait.

Advanced Functions and Closures
-------------------------------

the "fn" type is called a function pointer,we can passing functions with function
pointers to another function as its arguments.
    fn need_a_func(tf: fn());
to specify parameters for function pointer,we can list the types of its parameters.
    fn need_a_func(tf: fn(i32, u32, &String));
! Fn closure trait do not confused with "fn" type,"fn" is a type,not a trait,
  it can not be used in the generic type trait bound.
function pointers implement all three of the closure traits,Fn,FnMut,FnOnce.
so we can pass the function pointer as an argument for a function that expects
a closure.
    fn need_a_fnclosure<T>(callable: T)
    where
        T: Fn()
    {
        ...
        callable();
        ...
    }
    // need_fnclosure<>() can receives a function pointer,or a closure.
    // if we want the trait bound receives arguments,then we can list types
    // in the parameter list.
    //     fn need_a_fnclosure<T: Fn(u32)>(callable: T);
    // if we pass to the function a function pointer receives no parameter,
    // compiler will throws error.
    // if we pass to the function a closure,we can use wildcard '_' to ignore
    // the parameter.
    //     need_a_fnclosure(|_| ...);
! the name of each enum variant that also becomes an initializer function.
      let x = EnumType::Enumerator1();

in rust,closures are represented by traits,we can not return closures directly,
but we can use the "impl" keyword to return a trait object,then we can return
a closure from a function indirectly.
    fn return_closure() -> impl Fn(u32) -> u32 {
        |x: u32| x + 1
    }
! each closure is also its own distinct type,even functions' signatures are the
  same "impl Fn(u32) -> u32",the closures they returned are not the same type.
  return "impl <trait-name>" type,rust will creates a unioque opaque type,the 
  detail of this type is constructed by rust,it is not visible to us,even the 
  trait is same,the opaque types rust generates for each are distinct.
  to solve this problem,we can wrap the trait object in a Box pointer.
      fn return_closure() -> Box<dyn Fn(u32) -> u32> {
          ...
      }

      // same type,Box<...>.

      fn return_closure_move() -> Box<dyn Fn(u32) -> u32> {
          Box::new(move || ...);
      }

Macros
------

fundamentally,macros are a way of writing code that writes other code,which is
known as "metaprogramming".

for a function,its signature must declare the number and type of parameters the
function has,but for macro,can take a variable number of parameters.
macro expanding will happens at pre-processing phase,before compile the real
code,but a function can only be executed at runtime.

in rust,most widely used form of macros is "declarative macro".it allows us to
write something similar to a match-expression.
for define a macro,we need to use "macro_rules!" construct.
    #[macro_export]
    // defining macro vec!
    macro_rules! vec {
        // pattern.
        ( $( $x:expr ),* ) => {
            {
                // code will replace the macro.
                let mut temp_vec = vec::new();
                $(
                    temp_vec.push($x);
                )*
                temp_vec
            }
        }
    }
    // the simplified vec! macro.
    // there is only one pattern,if vec! failed to match it,
    // an error would be thrown by compiler.

#[macro_export]
    this attribute is used to indicates that this macro should be made available
    whenever the crate in which the macro is defined is brought into scope.
    # export the macro.

the pattern syntax,matched against rust code structure rather than values,thus
it is seem like a little weird.
pattern is included into '()',and symbol '$' can be used to declare a variable
in the macro system,that will contain the rust code matching the pattern.
'$x:expr' is a marco variable named @x match any rust expression,it captures
values that match the pattern.
comma ',' as a separator of instances,and '*' specifies the pattern matches zero
or more of whatever precedes the '*'.(like the regex expression * symbol)
    vec![0, 1, 2, 3]
    ||
    VV
    vec {
                       +-------------+--+--+
                       |             |  |  |
                       |             V  V  V
          <<<<<<<<<<<<<=             -- -- --
        ( $( $x:expr ),* ) match [0, 1, 2, 3]
             =======              -- 
                   |              ^   
                   |              |   
                   +--------------+   
                    $x:expr matches expressions 0 1 2 3
                    $(),*  matchesthe rust code [0, 1, 2, 3]

        => { # code block to replace.

            let temp_vec = vec::new();

            # for each $(),replace code to the following statement.
            # $x is the expression in the matched rust code.
            # it is 0 1 2 3
            $(
                temp_vec.push($x);
            )*
            # '*' means zero or more,depends on the matched patterns.
            --> temp_vec.push(0);
                temp_vec.push(1);
                temp_vec.push(2);
                temp_vec.push(3);

            # finally,we return ownership from this code block.
            temp_vec
        }
    }

the second form of macro is the procedural macro,which acts more like a function,
and is a type of procedure.
procedual macro accepts code as an input,operate on that code,and produce code
as an output.
three kind procedual macros
    1> custom "derive".
    2> attribute-like.
    3> function-like.
the procedural macro must be defined in its own crate with a special crate type.
    use proc_macro::TokenStream;

    #[custom_attribute_example]
    pub fn attr_example(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
        ...
    }
TokenStream represents a sequence of tokens.the source code that the macro is
operating on makes up the input TokenStream,and the code the macro produces is
the output TokenStream.
#[...] the attribute specifies which kind of procedural macro it is.

for a derive procedural macro,its crate usually has name "<crate name>_derive",
custom derive still a derive attribute can only be used on structs and enums.
    use proc_macro::TokenStream;
    use quote::quote;

    #[proc_macro_derive(<derive_macro_name>)]
    pub fn <procedural_marco_fn>(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
        let ast = syn::parse(input).unwrap();
        impl_<macro_name>(&ast)
    }

    // the "syn" crate parses rust code from a string into data structure that
    // we can perform operations on.
    // the "quote" crate turns "syn" data structures back into rust code.
    
    # for @derive_macro_name,if we defining a macro to implement a trait for
    # a certain type,the name should follow the style "<trait-name>_derive".
    # the detail of that trait should be defined in the crate "<trait-name>".
    # (convention)

    fn impl_<macro_name>(ast: &syn::DeriveInput) -> TokenStream {
        let idt = &ast.ident;
        let output = quote! {
            impl <trait-name> for #idt {
                fn <trait-function-name>() {
                    ...
                }
            }
        };
    }
    // '#' will turns the content in variable @idt to literal,like
    // the '#' in C and C++ macro.
    //     @idt == MyStruct 'struct name,as the type'
    //     #idt => MyStruct 'literal'
    // rust has a built-in macro named "stringify!",it takes a rust expression
    // and converts it into a string literal at compile time,we can refer @idt
    // and convert it into string literal.
    //     stringify!(#idt) => "#idt"

    #[derive(<derive_macro_name>)]
    struct MyStruct { }

    ||
    VV

    # quote! output.
                          # DeriveInput::ident from syn::parse().
                          # referred through #idt at above.
    impl <trait-name> for MyStruct {
        fn <trait-function-name>() {
            ...
        }
    }

the attribute-like macro similar to custom derive macro,but instead of generate
code for the "derive" attribute,it allow us to create new attribute,and the 
attribute can be applied to almost all items,not only structs and enums.
    #[proc_macro_attribute]
    pub fn <macro_attr_name>(...) -> ... {
        ...
    }

    #[<macro_attr_name>(...)]
    fn another_function() {
        ...
    }

the function-like macro define macro that look like function calls,similar to
macro_rules!,but more flexible than functions.
macro_rules! can only use match-like syntax in it,but function-like procedural
macro has no such restriction.
    #[proc_macro]
    pub fn <function_like_macro>(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
        ...
    }
it is not an attribute,instead,we can invoke it like a function,like the 
println! macro.


/************************** Additional *****************************************/

Some Useful Rust Stuff :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Determine what is the type of the result is
-------------------------------------------

a very useful method to determine the type of an object,is the compile error
trick.
    let _:() = <expression>;
compiler will throws error and tell us what the type of result of @expression is.

Command Line Arguments
----------------------

a rust program can receives some command line parameter passed by user,or read
some environment variables.
the rust standard library provides "env" module,in which some argument related
functions are exist.

std::env::args()
    this function can return an iterator points to the packaged command line
    arguments,it is the special type Args.
    we can invoke the method collect() on the Args object,convert arguments into
    a collection.
        // we annotate Vec<String>,to tell rust convert them to
        // a vector of strings.
        let args: Vec<String> = std::env::args().collect();
    ! the first argument has index _zero_ is the program's name.

another function can do this is named args_os(),its behaviour depends on OS,and
it should only be used for the case that arguments contain invalid Unicode.

std::env::var(@env-name)
    this function is used to check whether the environment variable has the name
    @env-name is set.
    it will return a Result object,in which,the value of that environment variable
    is wrapped into Ok().
    ! we can invoke is_ok() method of the Result object to get a boolean value
      to check whether result is Ok or Err.

String object
-------------

String object does support to a lot of useful methods.

std::string::String::lines()
    member method to convert context in the String object to 'newline' character
    separated substrings.

std::string::String::contains(@pattern)
    member method to check whether this String contains @pattern in its context.
    return true or false.
    @pattern could be another String object,or slice type object.

std::string::String::to_lowercase()
    member method to convert the context in this String object to lowercase
    characters.

! usually,the member methods of String object can also works on a slice object.

we can compare whether or not two string is the same in the if-statement through
the '==' operator,this also works for slice type.
    let str = "string..";

    // True
    if str == "string.." {
        ...
    }

File I/O
--------

the standard library provides module named "fs",it contains some filesystem
related stuff.

std::fs::read_to_string(@file_name)
    this function will open the file represented by @file_name,and read its
    contents into a String object.
    if succeed,return a Result<String> object.
    ! this function will saves the file's contents into a single String object.

Standard Error
--------------

generally,we print the message to the standard output stream,but sometimes,we
need to print error message to the stream different from stdout,the stderr.
for example,a program's output maybe redirected through shell operator '>' to
a file,but we need to ensure the error message is not contained in that file,
thus,we need to print error message to stderr instead print it to stdout.

eprintln!(@formatting-string, ...)
    different from println!(),the function eprintln!() will print the message
    to stderr.

exit() function
---------------

in rust,we usually do not explicitly invoke exit() or use return statement in the
main() function.
but sometimes,we might want to call exit() instead call to panic!() for the 
special case that program runs wrong.

std::process::exit(@exit_code)
    the @exit_code is type of i32.
    this function similar to the exit() function in C and C++.

TDD,Test-Driven Development
---------------------------

the test driven development process,is we build the core functionalities after
we have built the test module for those coming functionalities.

the process is >
    1> make test crate,it will fails,and it must fails for the reason we
       expect.
    2> make core crate for the test crate,and let the test pass.
    3> refactor core crate,and ensure the test continue to pass.
    4> repeat from 1>.

unimplemented!() macro
----------------------

this macro can be used as a placeholder for where the corresponding functionality
has not implemented.
it will let program panics with the message "not implemented".

while let loop
-------------------

the loop "while let" similar to "if let" statement,but this is for loop.
    while let <pattern> = <match> {
        ...
    }

we execute the loop,if we matched the pattern.

TCP Connection in Rust
----------------------

standard library contains module named "net",in which the type "TcpListener" can
be used to build a network endpoint over TCP.

bind(@endpoint) -> Result<TcpListener>
    the member function bind() can be used to register a TCP endpoint,it receives
    a string composed by ip address and port number "ip-address:port",return
    Result<> type.

incoming() -> Incoming<>
    member method incoming() start listening on the specified endpoint,and wait
    for client connection.
    if a connection is entablished,it will return an Incoming<> type,it is an
    iterator over the connections being received on this listener.
    we can unwrap() on the iterator to get the stream for current connection,
    next() on the iterator will advance this iterator to next connection.
    ! the stream is represents by TcpStream.

write_all(@bytes) -> Result<>
    member method write_all() of TcpStream can be used to write data to peer.

to read the stream,rust provides a type BufReader,we can pass reference to the
TcpStream to its new() method to construct an object is type of BufReader,then
we can use BufReader's methods to handle the stream.

lines() -> Lines<>
    BufReader implemented BufRead trait,thus method lines() also works on it.
    this method format stream to lines,the Lines<> type is an iterator over the
    lines.

map(@closure) -> Map<>
    method map() of Lines<> can be used to deal with each lines through the
    iterator,it will return Map<> type.the Map<> type is also an iterator over
    the mapped lines.

take_while(@predicate-closure) -> TakeWhile<>
    method take_while() of Map<> type can be used to create an iterator that
    yields elements based on a predicate.

collect() -> <ContainerType>
    method collect() of an iterator can be used to convert the sequence to a
    container type.
    ! used generic type.

HTTP Packet
------------

a HTTP request takes the following format.
    <HTTP Method> <Request-URI> <HTTP-Version><CRLF>
    <HTTP Headers><CRLF>
    <HTTP Message Body>

a HTTP respone takes the following format.
    <HTTP-Version> <HTTP-Status-Code> <Reason-Phrase><CRLF>
    <HTTP Headers><CRLF>
    <HTTP Message Body>

where CRLF is "carriage return and line feed".sequence "\r" means carriage return,
and sequence "\n" means line feed.
usually CRLF is "\r\n",but it is rarely to be printed.
! we usually insert another one CRLF between message body and headers.
      <header> <crlf>
      <crlf>
      <body>
    

